# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: aaron-c-waters
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:aaron-c-waters/aaron-c-waters] Waters was born as the youngest of seven children of parents who were pioneers in Washington state and grew wheat at their homestead.
[src:aaron-c-waters/aaron-c-waters] He graduated in geology from the University of Washington with a B.Sc. in 1927 and an M.Sc. in 1928.
[src:aaron-c-waters/aaron-c-waters] He graduated with a Ph.D. in geology in 1930 from Yale University.
[src:aaron-c-waters/aaron-c-waters] His doctoral dissertation *Geology of the Southern Half of the Chelan [30′] Quadrangle, Washington* was supervised by Adolph Knopf.
[src:aaron-c-waters/aaron-c-waters] From 1930 to 1951 Waters held an appointment as a faculty member at Stanford University.
[src:aaron-c-waters/aaron-c-waters] He was leave of absence for the arcademic year 1937–1938 and during WW II from 1942 to 1945.
[src:aaron-c-waters/aaron-c-waters] For the academic year 1937–1938 he was a Guggenheim Fellow and did research in Scotland and Scandinavia.
[src:aaron-c-waters/aaron-c-waters] In 1940 he married Elizabeth von Hoene, who was then a student at Mills College.
[src:aaron-c-waters/aaron-c-waters] During their marriage, she often accompanied him in his fieldwork and served as camp cook.
[src:aaron-c-waters/aaron-c-waters] After the attack on Pearl Harbor, the United States Geological Survey (USGS) expanded its search for strategic minerals.
[src:aaron-c-waters/aaron-c-waters] Waters went on an extended leave of absence to serve in the USGS — the main focus of his work was on mercury deposits.
[src:aaron-c-waters/aaron-c-waters] He first worked in Arkansas and then in several western states.
[src:aaron-c-waters/aaron-c-waters] Before the end of WW II he was sent to search for other metal ores in different parts of the USA.
[src:aaron-c-waters/aaron-c-waters] In 1945 he returned to his professorial duties at Stanford and began to focus on basalts and other volcanic rocks of the Pacific Northwest.
[src:aaron-c-waters/aaron-c-waters] Waters, in collaboration with James Gilluly and Alfred Woodford, wrote a textbook *Principles of Geology*, which was published by W.
[src:aaron-c-waters/aaron-c-waters] The *Principles of Geology* went through 4 editions and for more than two decades remained the leading introductory textbook for geology.
[src:aaron-c-waters/aaron-c-waters] Waters acquired expertise concerning uranium ores and from 1951 to 1952 participated in the USGS's exploration for uranium ores on the Colorado Plateau.
[src:aaron-c-waters/aaron-c-waters] In 1952 Waters resigned from Stanford University to accept an appointment at Johns Hopkins University, where he was a professor from 1952 to 1963.
[src:aaron-c-waters/aaron-c-waters] From 1963 to 1967 he was a professor and chair of the geology department at the University of California, Santa Barbara.
[src:aaron-c-waters/aaron-c-waters] From 1967 to 1972 he was a professor at the University of California, Santa Cruz.
[src:aaron-c-waters/aaron-c-waters] There he established a Ph.D. program in earth sciences and retired as professor emeritus in 1972.
[src:aaron-c-waters/aaron-c-waters] Santa Cruz, he worked with Richard Virgil Fisher on maar volcanism.
[src:aaron-c-waters/aaron-c-waters] In retirement as professor emeritus, Waters occasionally taught part-time at the University of Satan Cruz and held visiting professorships at Oregon State University, the University of Texas at El Paso, and California State University, Los Angeles.
[src:aaron-c-waters/aaron-c-waters] As professor emeritus, he also worked as a research consultant for the USGS and Los Alamos National Laboratory.
[src:aaron-c-waters/aaron-c-waters] Waters was elected in 1964 a Member of the National Academy of Sciences and in 1966 a Member of the American Academy of Arts and Sciences.
[src:aaron-c-waters/aaron-c-waters] In 1982 he was awarded the Penrose Medal of the Geological Society of America.
[src:aaron-c-waters/aaron-c-waters] In 1983 Aaron and Elizabeth Waters settled in Tacoma, where he continued to write about geology and pursue his hobby of gardening.
[src:aaron-c-waters/aaron-c-waters] Upon his death in 1991, he was survived by his widow, their two daughters, and three grandchildren.
[src:aaron-c-waters/aaron-c-waters] Waters was a leading expert on the geology of the Pacific Northwest.
[src:aaron-c-waters/aaron-c-waters] He did research on volcanology, igneous and metamorphic petrology, geomorphology, and tectonics.
[src:aaron-c-waters/aaron-c-waters] Krauskopf, he did important fieldwork on protoplastic deformation found in the Colville batholith.
[src:aaron-c-waters/aaron-c-waters] Waters was the author or co-author of classic articles on determining the directions of flow in volcanic rocks and on documenting the characteristics of volcanic base surge deposits.
[src:aaron-c-waters/aaron-c-waters] As a participant in the Apollo program, he contributed to research on lunar geology, including composition and origin of the lunar surface and assessment of Apollo landing sites.
[src:aaron-c-waters/aaron-c-waters] He was involved in the geological training of the astronauts, including those astronauts who later made lunar landings.
[src:aaron-c-waters/adolph-knopf] Knopf was a member of the National Academy of Sciences and the American Academy of Arts and Sciences.
[src:aaron-c-waters/adolph-knopf] He served as president of the Geological Society of America in 1944 and received its Penrose Medal in 1959.
[src:aaron-c-waters/adolph-knopf] His second wife, Eleanora Knopf, was a notable geologist and frequent collaborator.
[src:aaron-c-waters/adolph-knopf] Knopf was born December 2, 1882, in San Francisco, California, to German American immigrants.
[src:aaron-c-waters/adolph-knopf] He grew up with his family on a ranch near Woodside, California.
[src:aaron-c-waters/adolph-knopf] Knopf entered the University of California, Berkeley, where he became a student of petrology under Andrew Lawson.
[src:aaron-c-waters/adolph-knopf] He earned a Bachelor of Science degree in mining geology in 1904 and a Master of Science degree in 1905.
[src:aaron-c-waters/adolph-knopf] That same year he spent the first of six summers surveying the mineral deposits of Alaska for the United States Geological Survey (USGS).
[src:aaron-c-waters/adolph-knopf] In 1906 he moved to Washington, D.C., to work for the USGS full-time.
[src:aaron-c-waters/adolph-knopf] The Alaskan Division, of which Knopf was one of about a dozen members, was considered the best geologic group in the USGS at that time.
[src:aaron-c-waters/adolph-knopf] Knopf's work on tin deposits in the Seward Peninsula became the basis of the dissertation for his Ph.D., which he received from Berkeley in 1909.
[src:aaron-c-waters/adolph-knopf] In Alaska he also discovered the minerals hulsite and paigeite.
[src:aaron-c-waters/adolph-knopf] In 1911 Knopf was promoted from assistant geologist to geologist.
[src:aaron-c-waters/adolph-knopf] Over the next nine years he undertook a series of field projects for the USGS, beginning with the mining district in Montana that includes the Boulder Batholith and continuing to other western states including Nevada and California.
[src:aaron-c-waters/adolph-knopf] In the latter state he surveyed the Gold Country.
[src:aaron-c-waters/adolph-knopf] After discovering that universities on the eastern seaboard were paying about double the USGS salaries, Knopf left the USGS for a teaching position, and a number of his colleagues followed suit.
[src:aaron-c-waters/adolph-knopf] Knopf began at Yale University in January 1920.
[src:aaron-c-waters/adolph-knopf] He encouraged students to work with the USGS as he had done; this helped mitigate the agency's brain drain following the departures.
[src:aaron-c-waters/adolph-knopf] Knopf began at Yale as an associate professor but was promoted to full professor in 1923.
[src:aaron-c-waters/adolph-knopf] He was named the Silliman Professor of Geology in 1937 and a Sterling Professor in 1938.
[src:aaron-c-waters/adolph-knopf] He was director of graduate studies from 1933 until his retirement from Yale in 1951.
[src:aaron-c-waters/adolph-knopf] Upon retiring he returned to his native Woodside, California, settling not far from his family's old ranch.
[src:aaron-c-waters/adolph-knopf] There he accepted a visiting appointment at the Stanford University School of Earth Sciences, where he remained until his death in 1966.
[src:aaron-c-waters/adolph-knopf] Knopf's field work continued through his Yale and Stanford appointments, again with a focus on western states.
[src:aaron-c-waters/adolph-knopf] He continued his work in the Boulder Batholith and investigated intrusive igneous rock bodies in the Spanish Peaks in Colorado.
[src:aaron-c-waters/adolph-knopf] He also contributed to the emerging field of geochronology, putting lower bounds of 2 billion years and later 4.5 billion years on the age of the Earth.
[src:aaron-c-waters/adolph-knopf] Knopf was elected to the National Academy of Sciences in 1931.
[src:aaron-c-waters/adolph-knopf] He was also a Fellow of the American Academy of Arts and Sciences and of the Geological Society of America.
[src:aaron-c-waters/adolph-knopf] He was president of the Geological Society of America in 1944, and he received the Penrose Medal in 1959.
[src:aaron-c-waters/adolph-knopf] In 1937 he was vice president of the Society of Economic Geologists.
[src:aaron-c-waters/adolph-knopf] In 1908 Knopf married Agnes Burchard Dillon.
[src:aaron-c-waters/adolph-knopf] They had three daughters and one son, though one of the daughters died in infancy.
[src:aaron-c-waters/adolph-knopf] Agnes died in 1918 in that year's flu pandemic.
[src:aaron-c-waters/adolph-knopf] In June 1920, Knopf married fellow USGS geologist Eleanora Frances Bliss, who as Eleanora Knopf became a frequent collaborator and travel companion.
[src:aaron-c-waters/adolph-knopf] When Adolph moved to Yale, which did not then hire women, Eleanora worked out of Adolph's office, teaching private classes and still accepting USGS assignments.
[src:aaron-c-waters/adolph-knopf] When they moved to California, Stanford hired her as a research associate.
[src:aaron-c-waters/adolph-knopf] Knopf died November 23, 1966, in Palo Alto, California.
[src:aaron-c-waters/adolph-knopf] In his will he endowed a chaired professorship at Yale.
[src:aaron-c-waters/adolph-knopf] The sitting Adolph Knopf Professor of Petrology is Shun-ichiro Karato.
[src:aaron-c-waters/adolph-knopf] Adolph and Eleanora Knopf also endowed a graduate fellowship in petrology at Stanford.
[src:aaron-c-waters/adolph-knopf] Mount Adolph Knopf in Juneau Borough, Alaska is named after him.
[src:aaron-c-waters/alfred-woodford] Woodford was born in Upland, California, on February 27, 1890, to a family of successful citrus farmers.
[src:aaron-c-waters/alfred-woodford] He moved with his family to neighboring Claremont in 1909, and graduated from Pomona College (where he was editor of *The Student Life*) with a degree in chemistry in 1913.
[src:aaron-c-waters/alfred-woodford] He subsequently pursued graduate work in soil chemistry at the University of California, Berkeley, and received his doctorate in 1921.
[src:aaron-c-waters/alfred-woodford] Woodford joined the chemistry department at Pomona in 1915 or 1916, while he was pursuing his doctorate.
[src:aaron-c-waters/alfred-woodford] In 1919 or 1920, he began teaching geology, and he established the college's geology department in 1921 or 1922.
[src:aaron-c-waters/alfred-woodford] He was Pomona's sole geology professor for two decades, until his former student John Shelton joined him in 1941.
[src:aaron-c-waters/alfred-woodford] His academic specialties included California geology, stream hydraulics, and the history of geology.
[src:aaron-c-waters/alfred-woodford] Woodford taught many students who went on to have notable careers, including Rollin Eckis, Roger Revelle, Charles A.
[src:aaron-c-waters/alfred-woodford] Several were involved in California's oil industry.
[src:aaron-c-waters/alfred-woodford] From 1920 to 1940, Pomona graduated more geologists on a per capita basis who became listed in *American Men of Science* than any other institution.
[src:aaron-c-waters/alfred-woodford] In 1951, Woodford published a geology textbook with James Gilluly and Aaron C.
[src:aaron-c-waters/alfred-woodford] Waters, *Principles of Geology*, which became the standard instruction for the subject.
[src:aaron-c-waters/alfred-woodford] He published a history of the field, *Historical Geology*, in 1965.
[src:aaron-c-waters/alfred-woodford] Woodford married Gwendolyn Green in 1929, a partnership that lasted until her death in 1982.
[src:aaron-c-waters/alfred-woodford] He had two daughters, Marjorie and Betsy.
[src:aaron-c-waters/alfred-woodford] In his spare time, he played bridge and supported Pomona's athletics program.
[src:aaron-c-waters/alfred-woodford] Woodford retired from teaching in 1955, although he continued to engage with students into his 90s.
[src:aaron-c-waters/alfred-woodford] In 1972, he served as president of the National Association of Geologists.
[src:aaron-c-waters/alfred-woodford] A centenarian, he died on June 29, 1990, at Pilgrim Place, a retirement community in Claremont.
[src:aaron-c-waters/alfred-woodford] Upon his retirement, Woodford was awarded the Neil A.
[src:aaron-c-waters/alfred-woodford] Miner Award, the highest honor bestowed by the National Association of Geoscience Teachers.
[src:aaron-c-waters/alfred-woodford] In 1971, Pomona granted him an honorary doctorate.
[src:aaron-c-waters/american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences] The **American Academy of Arts and Sciences** (**The Academy**) is one of the oldest learned societies in the United States.
[src:aaron-c-waters/american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences] It was founded in 1780 during the American Revolution by John Adams, John Hancock, James Bowdoin, Andrew Oliver, and other Founding Fathers of the United States.
[src:aaron-c-waters/american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences] It is headquartered in Cambridge, Massachusetts.
[src:aaron-c-waters/american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences] Membership in the academy is achieved through a nominating petition, review, and election process.
[src:aaron-c-waters/american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences] The academy's quarterly journal, *Dædalus*, is published by the MIT Press on behalf of the academy, and has been open-access since January 2021.
[src:aaron-c-waters/american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences] The academy also conducts multidisciplinary public policy research.
[src:aaron-c-waters/american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences] Patton has served as President of the Academy since January 2025.
[src:aaron-c-waters/american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences] The first class of new members, chosen by the Academy in 1781, included Benjamin Franklin and George Washington as well as several international honorary members.
[src:aaron-c-waters/american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences] The initial volume of Academy *Memoirs* appeared in 1785, and the *Proceedings* followed in 1846.
[src:aaron-c-waters/american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences] In the 1950s, the Academy launched its journal *Daedalus*, reflecting its commitment to a broader intellectual and socially-oriented program.
[src:aaron-c-waters/american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences] Since the second half of the twentieth century, independent research has become a central focus of the Academy.
[src:aaron-c-waters/american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences] In the late 1950s, arms control emerged as one of its signature concerns.
[src:aaron-c-waters/american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences] The Academy also served as the catalyst in establishing the National Humanities Center in North Carolina.
[src:aaron-c-waters/american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences] In the late 1990s, the Academy developed a new strategic plan, focusing on four major areas: science, technology, and global security; social policy and education; humanities and culture; and education.
[src:aaron-c-waters/american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences] In 2002, the Academy established a visiting scholars program in association with Harvard University.
[src:aaron-c-waters/american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences] More than 75 academic institutions from across the country have become Affiliates of the Academy to support this program and other Academy initiatives.
[src:aaron-c-waters/american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences] The Academy has sponsored a number of awards and prizes, throughout its history and has offered opportunities for fellowships and visiting scholars at the Academy.
[src:aaron-c-waters/american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences] In July 2013, *The Boston Globe* exposed then president Leslie Berlowitz for falsifying her credentials, faking a doctorate, and consistently mistreating her staff.
[src:aaron-c-waters/american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences] It is modeled on the Science and Engineering Indicators, published biennially by the National Science Board as required by Congress.
[src:aaron-c-waters/american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences] Ever since the founding of the Academy, its members have been nominated and elected by peers.
[src:aaron-c-waters/american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences] Members of the Academy included not only scientists and scholars, but also writers and artists as well as representatives from the full range of professions and public life.
[src:aaron-c-waters/american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences] Throughout the Academy's history, more than 10,000 fellows have been elected.
[src:aaron-c-waters/american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences] Astronomer Maria Mitchell was the first woman elected to the Academy, in 1848.
[src:aaron-c-waters/american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences] The current membership encompasses over 5,700 members based across the United States and around the world.
[src:aaron-c-waters/american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences] Academy members include more than 250 Nobel laureates and more than 60 Pulitzer Prize winners.
[src:aaron-c-waters/american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences] Of the Academy's 14,343 members since 1780, 1,406 are or have been affiliated with Harvard University, 611 with the Massachusetts Institute of Technology, 433 with Yale University, 425 with the University of California, Berkeley, and 404 with Stanford University.
[src:aaron-c-waters/american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences] The following table includes those institutions affiliated with 300 or more members.
[src:aaron-c-waters/american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences] † Excludes members affiliated exclusively with associated national laboratories.
[src:aaron-c-waters/american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences] As of 2023, membership is divided into five classes and thirty specialties.
[src:aaron-c-waters/apollo-program-p01] The **Apollo program**, also known as **Project Apollo**, was the United States human spaceflight program led by NASA, which landed the first humans on the Moon in 1969.
[src:aaron-c-waters/apollo-program-p01] Apollo was conceived in 1960 in the Dwight D.
[src:aaron-c-waters/apollo-program-p01] Eisenhower presidency during Project Mercury and executed after Project Gemini.
[src:aaron-c-waters/apollo-program-p01] Apollo was later dedicated to President John F.
[src:aaron-c-waters/apollo-program-p01] Kennedy's national goal, "before this decade is out, of landing a man on the Moon and returning him safely to the Earth" in his address to the U.S.
[src:aaron-c-waters/apollo-program-p01] Approximately 650 million people worldwide watched this first landing on television.
[src:aaron-c-waters/apollo-program-p01] Five subsequent Apollo missions also landed astronauts on the Moon, the last, Apollo 17, in December 1972.
[src:aaron-c-waters/apollo-program-p01] In these six spaceflights, twelve people walked on the Moon.
[src:aaron-c-waters/apollo-program-p01] Apollo ran from 1961 to 1972, with the first crewed flight in 1968.
[src:aaron-c-waters/apollo-program-p01] It encountered a major setback in 1967 when the Apollo 1 cabin fire killed the entire crew during a prelaunch test.
[src:aaron-c-waters/apollo-program-p01] After the first Moon landing, sufficient flight hardware remained for nine follow-on landings with a plan for extended lunar geological and astrophysical exploration.
[src:aaron-c-waters/apollo-program-p01] Budget cuts forced the cancellation of three of these.
[src:aaron-c-waters/apollo-program-p01] Five of the remaining six missions achieved landings; but the Apollo 13 landing had to be aborted after an oxygen tank exploded en route to the Moon, crippling the CSM.
[src:aaron-c-waters/apollo-program-p01] The crew barely managed a safe return to Earth by using the Lunar Module as a "lifeboat" on the return journey.
[src:aaron-c-waters/apollo-program-p01] Apollo set several major human spaceflight milestones.
[src:aaron-c-waters/apollo-program-p01] It stands alone in sending humans to the lunar surface.
[src:aaron-c-waters/apollo-program-p01] Apollo 8 was the first crewed mission to leave low Earth orbit and to orbit another celestial body, and Apollo 11 was the first crewed mission to land humans on one.
[src:aaron-c-waters/apollo-program-p01] Overall, the Apollo program returned 842 pounds (382 kg) of lunar rocks to Earth, greatly contributing to the understanding of the Moon's composition and geological history.
[src:aaron-c-waters/apollo-program-p01] The program laid the foundation for NASA's subsequent human spaceflight capability and funded construction of its Johnson Space Center and Kennedy Space Center.
[src:aaron-c-waters/apollo-program-p01] Apollo also spurred advances in many areas of technology incidental to rocketry and human spaceflight, including avionics, telecommunications, and computers.
[src:aaron-c-waters/apollo-program-p01] Following the end of the Apollo program, humans would not leave low Earth orbit until the Artemis II flyby of the Moon in 2026, as part of the Artemis program, established as a successor to Apollo in 2017.
[src:aaron-c-waters/apollo-program-p01] Artemis intends to return humans to the Moon's surface no earlier than 2028.
[src:aaron-c-waters/apollo-program-p01] The context of this was that the program focused at its beginning mainly on developing an advanced crewed spacecraft, the Apollo command and service module, succeeding the Mercury program.
[src:aaron-c-waters/apollo-program-p01] A lunar landing became the focus of the program only in 1961.
[src:aaron-c-waters/apollo-program-p01] Thereafter Project Gemini instead followed the Mercury program to test and study advanced crewed spaceflight technology.
[src:aaron-c-waters/apollo-program-p01] The Apollo program was conceived during the Eisenhower administration in early 1960, as a follow-up to Project Mercury.
[src:aaron-c-waters/apollo-program-p01] While the Mercury capsule could support only one astronaut on a limited Earth orbital mission, Apollo would carry three.
[src:aaron-c-waters/apollo-program-p01] Possible missions included ferrying crews to a space station, circumlunar flights, and eventual crewed lunar landings.
[src:aaron-c-waters/apollo-program-p01] In July 1960, NASA Deputy Administrator Hugh L.
[src:aaron-c-waters/apollo-program-p01] Dryden announced the Apollo program to industry representatives at a series of Space Task Group conferences.
[src:aaron-c-waters/apollo-program-p01] Preliminary specifications were laid out for a spacecraft with a *mission module* cabin separate from the *command module* (piloting and reentry cabin), and a *propulsion and equipment module*.
[src:aaron-c-waters/apollo-program-p01] On August 30, a feasibility study competition was announced, and on October 25, three study contracts were awarded to General Dynamics/Convair, General Electric, and the Glenn L.
[src:aaron-c-waters/apollo-program-p01] Meanwhile, NASA performed its own in-house spacecraft design studies led by Maxime Faget, to serve as a gauge to judge and monitor the three industry designs.
[src:aaron-c-waters/apollo-program-p01] Kennedy was elected president after a campaign that promised American superiority over the Soviet Union in the fields of space exploration and missile defense.
[src:aaron-c-waters/apollo-program-p01] Up to the election of 1960, Kennedy had been speaking out against the "missile gap" that he and many other senators said had developed between the Soviet Union and the United States due to the inaction of President Eisenhower.
[src:aaron-c-waters/apollo-program-p01] Beyond military power, Kennedy used aerospace technology as a symbol of national prestige, pledging to make the US not "first but, first and, first if, but first period".
[src:aaron-c-waters/apollo-program-p01] Despite Kennedy's rhetoric, he did not immediately come to a decision on the status of the Apollo program once he became president.
[src:aaron-c-waters/apollo-program-p01] He knew little about the technical details of the space program, and was put off by the massive financial commitment required by a crewed Moon landing.
[src:aaron-c-waters/apollo-program-p01] When Kennedy's newly appointed NASA Administrator James E.
[src:aaron-c-waters/apollo-program-p01] Webb requested a 30 percent budget increase for his agency, Kennedy supported an acceleration of NASA's large booster program but deferred a decision on the broader issue.
[src:aaron-c-waters/apollo-program-p01] On April 12, 1961, Soviet cosmonaut Yuri Gagarin became the first person to fly in space, reinforcing American fears about being left behind in a technological competition with the Soviet Union.
[src:aaron-c-waters/apollo-program-p01] At a meeting of the US House Committee on Science and Astronautics one day after Gagarin's flight, many congressmen pledged their support for a crash program aimed at ensuring that America would catch up.
[src:aaron-c-waters/apollo-program-p01] Kennedy was circumspect in his response to the news, refusing to make a commitment on America's response to the Soviets.
[src:aaron-c-waters/apollo-program-p01] On April 20, Kennedy sent a memo to Vice President Lyndon B.
[src:aaron-c-waters/apollo-program-p01] Johnson, asking Johnson to look into the status of America's space program, and into programs that could offer NASA the opportunity to catch up.
[src:aaron-c-waters/apollo-program-p01] At the time of Kennedy's proposal, only one American had flown in space—less than a month earlier—and NASA had not yet sent an astronaut into orbit.
[src:aaron-c-waters/apollo-program-p01] Even some NASA employees doubted whether Kennedy's ambitious goal could be met.
[src:aaron-c-waters/apollo-program-p01] By 1963, Kennedy even came close to agreeing to a joint US-USSR Moon mission, to eliminate duplication of effort.
[src:aaron-c-waters/apollo-program-p01] The mission module was determined to be useful only as an extra room, and therefore unnecessary.
[src:aaron-c-waters/apollo-program-p01] They used Faget's design as the specification for another competition for spacecraft procurement bids in October 1961.
[src:aaron-c-waters/apollo-program-p01] On November 28, 1961, North American Aviation won the contract, although its bid was not rated as good as the Martin proposal.
[src:aaron-c-waters/apollo-program-p01] Webb, Dryden and Robert Seamans chose it in preference due to North American's longer association with NASA and its predecessor.
[src:aaron-c-waters/apollo-program-p01] Landing humans on the Moon by the end of 1969 required the most sudden burst of technological creativity, and the largest commitment of resources ($25 billion; $187 billion in 2024 US dollars) ever made by any nation in peacetime.
[src:aaron-c-waters/apollo-program-p01] At its peak, the Apollo program employed 400,000 people and required the support of over 20,000 industrial firms and universities.
[src:aaron-c-waters/apollo-program-p01] On July 1, 1960, NASA established the Marshall Space Flight Center (MSFC) in Huntsville, Alabama.
[src:aaron-c-waters/apollo-program-p01] MSFC designed the heavy lift-class Saturn launch vehicles, which would be required for Apollo.
[src:aaron-c-waters/apollo-program-p01] It became clear that managing the Apollo program would exceed the capabilities of Robert R.
[src:aaron-c-waters/apollo-program-p01] Gilruth's Space Task Group, which had been directing the nation's crewed space program from NASA's Langley Research Center.
[src:aaron-c-waters/apollo-program-p01] So Gilruth was given authority to grow his organization into a new NASA center, the Manned Spacecraft Center (MSC).
[src:aaron-c-waters/apollo-program-p01] A site was chosen in Houston, Texas, on land donated by Rice University, and Administrator Webb announced the conversion on September 19, 1961.
[src:aaron-c-waters/apollo-program-p01] It was also clear NASA would soon outgrow its practice of controlling missions from its Cape Canaveral Air Force Station launch facilities in Florida, so a new Mission Control Center would be included in the MSC.
[src:aaron-c-waters/apollo-program-p01] The MSC was completed in September 1963.
[src:aaron-c-waters/apollo-program-p01] It was renamed by the United States Congress in honor of Lyndon B.
[src:aaron-c-waters/apollo-program-p01] It also became clear that Apollo would outgrow the Canaveral launch facilities in Florida.
[src:aaron-c-waters/apollo-program-p01] The two newest launch complexes were already being built for the Saturn I and IB rockets at the northernmost end: LC-34 and LC-37.
[src:aaron-c-waters/apollo-program-p01] An even bigger facility was needed for the mammoth rocket required for the crewed lunar mission, so land acquisition was started in July 1961 for a Launch Operations Center (LOC) immediately north of Canaveral at Merritt Island.
[src:aaron-c-waters/apollo-program-p01] The design, development and construction of the center was conducted by Kurt H.
[src:aaron-c-waters/apollo-program-p01] Debus, a member of Wernher von Braun's original V-2 rocket engineering team.
[src:aaron-c-waters/apollo-program-p01] Debus was named the LOC's first Director.
[src:aaron-c-waters/apollo-program-p01] Following Kennedy's death, President Johnson issued an executive order on November 29, 1963, to rename the LOC and Cape Canaveral in honor of Kennedy.
[src:aaron-c-waters/apollo-program-p01] Although at least three pads were planned, only two, designated A and B, were completed in October 1965.
[src:aaron-c-waters/apollo-program-p01] The LOC also included an Operations and Checkout Building (OCB) to which Gemini and Apollo spacecraft were initially received prior to being mated to their launch vehicles.
[src:aaron-c-waters/apollo-program-p01] The Apollo spacecraft could be tested in two vacuum chambers capable of simulating atmospheric pressure at altitudes up to 250,000 feet (76 km), which is nearly a vacuum.
[src:aaron-c-waters/apollo-program-p01] Administrator Webb realized that in order to keep Apollo costs under control, he had to develop greater project management skills in his organization, so he recruited George E.
[src:aaron-c-waters/apollo-program-p01] Mueller accepted, on the condition that he have a say in NASA reorganization necessary to effectively administer Apollo.
[src:aaron-c-waters/apollo-program-p01] Webb then worked with Associate Administrator (later Deputy Administrator) Seamans to reorganize the Office of Manned Space Flight (OMSF).
[src:aaron-c-waters/apollo-program-p01] On July 23, 1963, Webb announced Mueller's appointment as Deputy Associate Administrator for Manned Space Flight, to replace then Associate Administrator D.
[src:aaron-c-waters/apollo-program-p01] Brainerd Holmes on his retirement effective September 1.
[src:aaron-c-waters/apollo-program-p01] Under Webb's reorganization, the directors of the Manned Spacecraft Center (Gilruth), Marshall Space Flight Center (von Braun), and the Launch Operations Center (Debus) reported to Mueller.
[src:aaron-c-waters/apollo-program-p01] Based on his industry experience on Air Force missile projects, Mueller realized some skilled managers could be found among high-ranking officers in the U.S.
[src:aaron-c-waters/apollo-program-p01] Air Force, so he got Webb's permission to recruit General Samuel C.
[src:aaron-c-waters/apollo-program-p01] Phillips, who gained a reputation for his effective management of the Minuteman program, as OMSF program controller.
[src:aaron-c-waters/apollo-program-p01] Schriever agreed to loan Phillips to NASA, along with a staff of officers under him, on the condition that Phillips be made Apollo Program Director.
[src:aaron-c-waters/apollo-program-p01] Mueller agreed, and Phillips managed Apollo from January 1964, until it achieved the first human landing in July 1969, after which he returned to Air Force duty.
[src:aaron-c-waters/apollo-program-p01] Charles Fishman, in *One Giant Leap*, estimated the number of people and organizations involved into the Apollo program as "410,000 men and women at some 20,000 different companies contributed to the effort".
[src:aaron-c-waters/apollo-program-p01] Once Kennedy had defined a goal, the Apollo mission planners were faced with the challenge of designing a spacecraft that could meet it while minimizing risk to human life, limiting cost, and not exceeding limits in possible technology and astronaut skill.
[src:aaron-c-waters/apollo-program-p01] In early 1961, direct ascent was generally the mission mode in favor at NASA.
[src:aaron-c-waters/apollo-program-p01] Many engineers feared that rendezvous and docking, maneuvers that had not been attempted in Earth orbit, would be nearly impossible in lunar orbit.
[src:aaron-c-waters/apollo-program-p01] LOR advocates—including Tom Dolan at Vought and John Houbolt at Langley Research Center—emphasized the important weight reductions that were offered by the LOR approach.
[src:aaron-c-waters/apollo-program-p01] Throughout 1960 and 1961, Houbolt campaigned for the recognition of LOR as a viable and practical option.
[src:aaron-c-waters/apollo-program-p01] Bypassing the NASA hierarchy, he sent a series of memos and reports on the issue to Associate Administrator Robert Seamans; while acknowledging that he spoke "somewhat as a voice in the wilderness", Houbolt pleaded that LOR should not be discounted in studies of the question.
[src:aaron-c-waters/apollo-program-p01] Seamans's establishment of an ad hoc committee headed by his special technical assistant Nicholas E.
[src:aaron-c-waters/apollo-program-p01] Golovin in July 1961, to recommend a launch vehicle to be used in the Apollo program, represented a turning point in NASA's mission mode decision.
[src:aaron-c-waters/apollo-program-p01] This committee recognized that the chosen mode was an important part of the launch vehicle choice, and recommended in favor of a hybrid EOR-LOR mode.
[src:aaron-c-waters/apollo-program-p01] Its consideration of LOR—as well as Houbolt's ceaseless work—played an important role in publicizing the workability of the approach.
[src:aaron-c-waters/apollo-program-p01] In late 1961 and early 1962, members of the Manned Spacecraft Center began to come around to support LOR, including the newly hired deputy director of the Office of Manned Space Flight, Joseph Shea, who became a champion of LOR.
[src:aaron-c-waters/apollo-program-p01] The engineers at Marshall Space Flight Center (MSFC), who were heavily invested in direct ascent, took longer to become convinced of its merits, but their conversion was announced by Wernher von Braun at a briefing on June 7, 1962.
[src:aaron-c-waters/apollo-program-p01] Even after NASA reached internal agreement, it was far from smooth sailing.
[src:aaron-c-waters/apollo-program-p01] Wiesner kept up the pressure, even making the disagreement public during a two-day September visit by the President to Marshall Space Flight Center.
[src:aaron-c-waters/apollo-program-p01] Wiesner blurted out "No, that's no good" in front of the press, during a presentation by von Braun.
[src:aaron-c-waters/apollo-program-p01] Webb jumped in and defended von Braun, until Kennedy ended the squabble by stating that the matter was "still subject to final review".
[src:aaron-c-waters/apollo-program-p01] Webb held firm and issued a request for proposal to candidate Lunar Excursion Module (LEM) contractors.
[src:aaron-c-waters/apollo-program-p01] Wiesner finally relented, unwilling to settle the dispute once and for all in Kennedy's office, because of the President's involvement with the October Cuban Missile Crisis, and fear of Kennedy's support for Webb.
[src:aaron-c-waters/apollo-program-p01] NASA announced the selection of Grumman as the LEM contractor in November 1962.
[src:aaron-c-waters/apollo-program-p01] The LOR method had the advantage of allowing the lander spacecraft to be used as a "lifeboat" in the event of a failure of the command ship.
[src:aaron-c-waters/apollo-program-p01] Some documents prove this theory was discussed before and after the method was chosen.
[src:aaron-c-waters/apollo-program-p01] In 1964 an MSC study concluded, "The LM [as lifeboat] ... was finally dropped, because no single reasonable CSM failure could be identified that would prohibit use of the SPS." That type of failure happened on Apollo 13 when an oxygen tank explosion left the CSM without electrical power.
[src:aaron-c-waters/apollo-program-p01] The lunar module provided propulsion, electrical power and life support to get the crew home safely.
[src:aaron-c-waters/apollo-program-p01] Faget's preliminary Apollo design employed a cone-shaped command module, supported by one of several service modules providing propulsion and electrical power, sized appropriately for the space station, cislunar, and lunar landing missions.
[src:aaron-c-waters/apollo-program-p01] Once Kennedy's Moon landing goal became official, detailed design began of a command and service module (CSM) in which the crew would spend the entire direct-ascent mission and lift off from the lunar surface for the return trip, after being soft-landed by a larger landing propulsion module.
[src:aaron-c-waters/apollo-program-p01] The command module (CM) was the conical crew cabin, designed to carry three astronauts from launch to lunar orbit and back to an Earth ocean landing.
[src:aaron-c-waters/apollo-program-p01] It was the only component of the Apollo spacecraft to survive without major configuration changes as the program evolved from the early Apollo study designs.
[src:aaron-c-waters/apollo-program-p01] Its exterior was covered with an ablative heat shield, and had its own reaction control system (RCS) engines to control its attitude and steer its atmospheric entry path.
[src:aaron-c-waters/apollo-program-p01] Parachutes were carried to slow its descent to splashdown.
[src:aaron-c-waters/apollo-program-p01] A cylindrical service module (SM) supported the command module, with a service propulsion engine and an RCS with propellants, and a fuel cell power generation system with liquid hydrogen and liquid oxygen reactants.
[src:aaron-c-waters/apollo-program-p01] A high-gain S-band antenna was used for long-distance communications on the lunar flights.
[src:aaron-c-waters/apollo-program-p01] On the extended lunar missions, an orbital scientific instrument package was carried.
[src:aaron-c-waters/apollo-program-p01] The service module was discarded just before reentry.
[src:aaron-c-waters/apollo-program-p01] The initial lunar flight version weighed approximately 51,300 pounds (23,300 kg) fully fueled, while a later version designed to carry a lunar orbit scientific instrument package weighed just over 54,000 pounds (24,000 kg).
[src:aaron-c-waters/apollo-program-p01] North American Aviation won the contract to build the CSM, and also the second stage of the Saturn V launch vehicle for NASA.
[src:aaron-c-waters/apollo-program-p01] Because the CSM design was started early before the selection of lunar orbit rendezvous, the service propulsion engine was sized to lift the CSM off the Moon, and thus was oversized to about twice the thrust required for translunar flight.
[src:aaron-c-waters/apollo-program-p01] Also, there was no provision for docking with the lunar module.
[src:aaron-c-waters/apollo-program-p01] A 1964 program definition study concluded that the initial design should be continued as Block I which would be used for early testing, while Block II, the actual lunar spacecraft, would incorporate the docking equipment and take advantage of the lessons learned in Block I development.
[src:aaron-c-waters/apollo-program-p01] The Apollo Lunar Module (LM) was designed to descend from lunar orbit to land two astronauts on the Moon and take them back to orbit to rendezvous with the command module.
[src:aaron-c-waters/apollo-program-p01] Not designed to fly through the Earth's atmosphere or return to Earth, its fuselage was designed totally without aerodynamic considerations and was of an extremely lightweight construction.
[src:aaron-c-waters/apollo-program-p01] It consisted of separate descent and ascent stages, each with its own engine.
[src:aaron-c-waters/apollo-program-p01] The descent stage contained storage for the descent propellant, surface stay consumables, and surface exploration equipment.
[src:aaron-c-waters/apollo-program-p01] The ascent stage contained the crew cabin, ascent propellant, and a reaction control system.
[src:aaron-c-waters/apollo-program-p01] The initial LM model weighed approximately 33,300 pounds (15,100 kg), and allowed surface stays up to around 34 hours.
[src:aaron-c-waters/apollo-program-p01] An extended lunar module (ELM) weighed over 36,200 pounds (16,400 kg), and allowed surface stays of more than three days.
[src:aaron-c-waters/apollo-program-p01] The contract for design and construction of the lunar module was awarded to Grumman Aircraft Engineering Corporation, and the project was overseen by Thomas J.
[src:aaron-c-waters/apollo-program-p01] Before the Apollo program began, Wernher von Braun and his team of rocket engineers had started work on plans for very large launch vehicles, the Saturn series, and the even larger Nova series.
[src:aaron-c-waters/apollo-program-p01] In the midst of these plans, von Braun was transferred from the Army to NASA and was made Director of the Marshall Space Flight Center.
[src:aaron-c-waters/apollo-program-p01] The initial direct ascent plan to send the three-person Apollo command and service module directly to the lunar surface, on top of a large descent rocket stage, would require a Nova-class launcher, with a lunar payload capability of over 180,000 pounds (82,000 kg).
[src:aaron-c-waters/apollo-program-p01] The June 11, 1962, decision to use lunar orbit rendezvous enabled the Saturn V to replace the Nova, and the MSFC proceeded to develop the Saturn rocket family for Apollo.
[src:aaron-c-waters/apollo-program-p01] This was changed by the time human flights began.
[src:aaron-c-waters/apollo-program-p01] Since Apollo, like Mercury, would require a launch escape system (LES) in case of a launch failure, a relatively small rocket was required for qualification flight testing of this system.
[src:aaron-c-waters/apollo-program-p01] A rocket bigger than the Little Joe used by Mercury would be required, so the Little Joe II was built by General Dynamics/Convair.
[src:aaron-c-waters/apollo-program-p01] After an August 1963 qualification test flight, four LES test flights (A-001 through 004) were made at the White Sands Missile Range between May 1964 and January 1966.
[src:aaron-c-waters/apollo-program-p01] Saturn I, the first US heavy lift launch vehicle, was initially planned to launch partially equipped CSMs in low Earth orbit tests.
[src:aaron-c-waters/apollo-program-p01] The S-I first stage burned RP-1 with liquid oxygen (LOX) oxidizer in eight clustered Rocketdyne H-1 engines, to produce 1,500,000 pounds-force (6,670 kN) of thrust.
[src:aaron-c-waters/apollo-program-p01] The S-IV second stage used six liquid hydrogen-fueled Pratt & Whitney RL-10 engines with 90,000 pounds-force (400 kN) of thrust.
[src:aaron-c-waters/apollo-program-p01] The S-V third stage flew inactively on Saturn I four times.
[src:aaron-c-waters/apollo-program-p01] The first four Saturn I test flights were launched from LC-34, with only the first stage live, carrying dummy upper stages filled with water.
[src:aaron-c-waters/apollo-program-p01] The first flight with a live S-IV was launched from LC-37.
[src:aaron-c-waters/apollo-program-p01] This was followed by five launches of boilerplate CSMs (designated AS-101 through AS-105) into orbit in 1964 and 1965.
[src:aaron-c-waters/apollo-program-p01] The last three of these further supported the Apollo program by also carrying Pegasus satellites, which verified the safety of the translunar environment by measuring the frequency and severity of micrometeorite impacts.
[src:aaron-c-waters/apollo-program-p01] In September 1962, NASA planned to launch four crewed CSM flights on the Saturn I from late 1965 through 1966, concurrent with Project Gemini.
[src:aaron-c-waters/apollo-program-p01] The 22,500-pound (10,200 kg) payload capacity would have severely limited the systems which could be included, so the decision was made in October 1963 to use the uprated Saturn IB for all crewed Earth orbital flights.
[src:aaron-c-waters/apollo-program-p01] The Saturn IB was an upgraded version of the Saturn I.
[src:aaron-c-waters/apollo-program-p01] The S-IB first stage increased the thrust to 1,600,000 pounds-force (7,120 kN) by uprating the H-1 engine.
[src:aaron-c-waters/apollo-program-p01] The second stage replaced the S-IV with the S-IVB-200, powered by a single J-2 engine burning liquid hydrogen fuel with LOX, to produce 200,000 pounds-force (890 kN) of thrust.
[src:aaron-c-waters/apollo-program-p01] A restartable version of the S-IVB was used as the third stage of the Saturn V.
[src:aaron-c-waters/apollo-program-p01] The Saturn IB could send over 40,000 pounds (18,100 kg) into low Earth orbit, sufficient for a partially fueled CSM or the LM.
[src:aaron-c-waters/apollo-program-p01] Saturn IB launch vehicles and flights were designated with an AS-200 series number, "AS" indicating "Apollo Saturn" and the "2" indicating the second member of the Saturn rocket family.
[src:aaron-c-waters/apollo-program-p01] Saturn V launch vehicles and flights were designated with an AS-500 series number, "AS" indicating "Apollo Saturn" and the "5" indicating Saturn V.
[src:aaron-c-waters/apollo-program-p01] The three-stage Saturn V was designed to send a fully fueled CSM and LM to the Moon.
[src:aaron-c-waters/apollo-program-p01] Its capability grew to 103,600 pounds (47,000 kg) for the later advanced lunar landings.
[src:aaron-c-waters/apollo-program-p01] The S-IC first stage burned RP-1/LOX for a rated thrust of 7,500,000 pounds-force (33,400 kN), which was upgraded to 7,610,000 pounds-force (33,900 kN).
[src:aaron-c-waters/apollo-program-p01] The second and third stages burned liquid hydrogen; the third stage was a modified version of the S-IVB, with thrust increased to 230,000 pounds-force (1,020 kN) and capability to restart the engine for translunar injection after reaching a parking orbit.
[src:aaron-c-waters/apollo-program-p01] NASA's director of flight crew operations during the Apollo program was Donald K.
[src:aaron-c-waters/apollo-program-p01] "Deke" Slayton, one of the original Mercury Seven astronauts who was medically grounded in September 1962 due to a heart murmur.
[src:aaron-c-waters/apollo-program-p01] Slayton was responsible for making all Gemini and Apollo crew assignments.
[src:aaron-c-waters/apollo-program-p01] Thirty-two astronauts were assigned to fly missions in the Apollo program.
[src:aaron-c-waters/apollo-program-p01] Twenty-four of these left Earth's orbit and flew around the Moon between December 1968 and December 1972 (three of them twice).
[src:aaron-c-waters/apollo-program-p01] Half of the 24 walked on the Moon's surface, though none of them returned to it after landing once.
[src:aaron-c-waters/apollo-program-p01] One of the moonwalkers was a trained geologist.
[src:aaron-c-waters/apollo-program-p01] Of the 32, Gus Grissom, Ed White, and Roger Chaffee were killed during a ground test in preparation for the Apollo 1 mission.
[src:aaron-c-waters/apollo-program-p01] The Apollo astronauts were chosen from the Project Mercury and Gemini veterans, plus from two later astronaut groups.
[src:aaron-c-waters/apollo-program-p01] All missions were commanded by Gemini or Mercury veterans.
[src:aaron-c-waters/apollo-program-p01] Crews on all development flights (except the Earth orbit CSM development flights) through the first two landings on Apollo 11 and Apollo 12, included at least two (sometimes three) Gemini veterans.
[src:aaron-c-waters/apollo-program-p01] Harrison Schmitt, a geologist, was the first NASA scientist astronaut to fly in space, and landed on the Moon on the last mission, Apollo 17.
[src:aaron-c-waters/apollo-program-p01] Schmitt participated in the lunar geology training of all of the Apollo landing crews.
[src:aaron-c-waters/apollo-program-p01] NASA awarded all 32 of these astronauts its highest honor, the Distinguished Service Medal, given for "distinguished service, ability, or courage", and personal "contribution representing substantial progress to the NASA mission".
[src:aaron-c-waters/apollo-program-p01] The medals were awarded posthumously to Grissom, White, and Chaffee in 1969, then to the crews of all missions from Apollo 8 onward.
[src:aaron-c-waters/apollo-program-p01] The crew that flew the first Earth orbital test mission Apollo 7, Walter M.
[src:aaron-c-waters/apollo-program-p01] Schirra, Donn Eisele, and Walter Cunningham, were awarded the lesser NASA Exceptional Service Medal, because of discipline problems with the flight director's orders during their flight.
[src:aaron-c-waters/apollo-program-p01] In October 2008, the NASA Administrator decided to award them the Distinguished Service Medals.
[src:aaron-c-waters/apollo-program-p01] For Schirra and Eisele, this was posthumously.
[src:aaron-c-waters/apollo-program-p02] Two Block I CSMs were launched from LC-34 on suborbital flights in 1966 with the Saturn IB.
[src:aaron-c-waters/apollo-program-p02] The first, AS-201 launched on February 26, reached an altitude of 265.7 nautical miles (492.1 km) and splashed down 4,577 nautical miles (8,477 km) downrange in the Atlantic Ocean.
[src:aaron-c-waters/apollo-program-p02] The second, AS-202 on August 25, reached 617.1 nautical miles (1,142.9 km) altitude and was recovered 13,900 nautical miles (25,700 km) downrange in the Pacific Ocean.
[src:aaron-c-waters/apollo-program-p02] These flights validated the service module engine and the command module heat shield.
[src:aaron-c-waters/apollo-program-p02] A third Saturn IB test, AS-203 launched from pad 37, went into orbit to support design of the S-IVB upper stage restart capability needed for the Saturn V.
[src:aaron-c-waters/apollo-program-p02] It carried a nose cone instead of the Apollo spacecraft, and its payload was the unburned liquid hydrogen fuel, the behavior of which engineers measured with temperature and pressure sensors, and a TV camera.
[src:aaron-c-waters/apollo-program-p02] This flight occurred on July 5, before AS-202, which was delayed because of problems getting the Apollo spacecraft ready for flight.
[src:aaron-c-waters/apollo-program-p02] Two crewed orbital Block I CSM missions were planned: AS-204 and AS-205.
[src:aaron-c-waters/apollo-program-p02] The Block I crew positions were titled Command Pilot, Senior Pilot, and Pilot.
[src:aaron-c-waters/apollo-program-p02] The Senior Pilot would assume navigation duties, while the Pilot would function as a systems engineer.
[src:aaron-c-waters/apollo-program-p02] The astronauts would wear a modified version of the Gemini spacesuit.
[src:aaron-c-waters/apollo-program-p02] After an uncrewed LM test flight AS-206, a crew would fly the first Block II CSM and LM in a dual mission known as AS-207/208, or AS-278 (each spacecraft would be launched on a separate Saturn IB).
[src:aaron-c-waters/apollo-program-p02] The Block II crew positions were titled Commander, Command Module Pilot, and Lunar Module Pilot.
[src:aaron-c-waters/apollo-program-p02] The astronauts would begin wearing a new Apollo A6L spacesuit, designed to accommodate lunar extravehicular activity (EVA).
[src:aaron-c-waters/apollo-program-p02] The traditional visor helmet was replaced with a clear "fishbowl" type for greater visibility, and the lunar surface EVA suit would include a water-cooled undergarment.
[src:aaron-c-waters/apollo-program-p02] Deke Slayton, the grounded Mercury astronaut who became director of flight crew operations for the Gemini and Apollo programs, selected the first Apollo crew in January 1966, with Grissom as Command Pilot, White as Senior Pilot, and rookie Donn F.
[src:aaron-c-waters/apollo-program-p02] But Eisele dislocated his shoulder twice aboard the KC135 weightlessness training aircraft, and had to undergo surgery on January 27.
[src:aaron-c-waters/apollo-program-p02] NASA announced the final crew selection for AS-204 on March 21, 1966, with the backup crew consisting of Gemini veterans James McDivitt and David Scott, with rookie Russell L.
[src:aaron-c-waters/apollo-program-p02] Mercury/Gemini veteran Wally Schirra, Eisele, and rookie Walter Cunningham were announced on September 29 as the prime crew for AS-205.
[src:aaron-c-waters/apollo-program-p02] In December 1966, the AS-205 mission was canceled, since the validation of the CSM would be accomplished on the 14-day first flight, and AS-205 would have been devoted to space experiments and contribute no new engineering knowledge about the spacecraft.
[src:aaron-c-waters/apollo-program-p02] Its Saturn IB was allocated to the dual mission, now redesignated AS-205/208 or AS-258, planned for August 1967.
[src:aaron-c-waters/apollo-program-p02] McDivitt, Scott and Schweickart were promoted to the prime AS-258 crew, and Schirra, Eisele and Cunningham were reassigned as the Apollo 1 backup crew.
[src:aaron-c-waters/apollo-program-p02] Eventually, the planned AS-204 flight date was pushed to February 21, 1967.
[src:aaron-c-waters/apollo-program-p02] North American Aviation was prime contractor not only for the Apollo CSM, but for the Saturn V S-II second stage as well, and delays in this stage pushed the first uncrewed Saturn V flight AS-501 from late 1966 to November 1967.
[src:aaron-c-waters/apollo-program-p02] The problems with North American were severe enough in late 1965 to cause Manned Space Flight Administrator George Mueller to appoint program director Samuel Phillips to head a "tiger team" to investigate North American's problems and identify corrections.
[src:aaron-c-waters/apollo-program-p02] Phillips documented his findings in a December 19 letter to NAA president Lee Atwood, with a strongly worded letter by Mueller, and also gave a presentation of the results to Mueller and Deputy Administrator Robert Seamans.
[src:aaron-c-waters/apollo-program-p02] Meanwhile, Grumman was also encountering problems with the Lunar Module, eliminating hopes it would be ready for crewed flight in 1967, not long after the first crewed CSM flights.
[src:aaron-c-waters/apollo-program-p02] Grissom, White, and Chaffee decided to name their flight Apollo 1 as a motivational focus on the first crewed flight.
[src:aaron-c-waters/apollo-program-p02] They trained and conducted tests of their spacecraft at North American, and in the altitude chamber at the Kennedy Space Center.
[src:aaron-c-waters/apollo-program-p02] A "plugs-out" test was planned for January, which would simulate a launch countdown on LC-34 with the spacecraft transferring from pad-supplied to internal power.
[src:aaron-c-waters/apollo-program-p02] If successful, this would be followed by a more rigorous countdown simulation test closer to the February 21 launch, with both spacecraft and launch vehicle fueled.
[src:aaron-c-waters/apollo-program-p02] The plugs-out test began on the morning of January 27, 1967, and immediately was plagued with problems.
[src:aaron-c-waters/apollo-program-p02] First, the crew noticed a strange odor in their spacesuits which delayed the sealing of the hatch.
[src:aaron-c-waters/apollo-program-p02] Then, communications problems frustrated the astronauts and forced a hold in the simulated countdown.
[src:aaron-c-waters/apollo-program-p02] During this hold, an electrical fire began in the cabin and spread quickly in the high pressure, 100% oxygen atmosphere.
[src:aaron-c-waters/apollo-program-p02] Pressure rose high enough from the fire that the cabin inner wall burst, allowing the fire to erupt onto the pad area and frustrating attempts to rescue the crew.
[src:aaron-c-waters/apollo-program-p02] The astronauts were asphyxiated before the hatch could be opened.
[src:aaron-c-waters/apollo-program-p02] NASA immediately convened an accident review board, overseen by both houses of Congress.
[src:aaron-c-waters/apollo-program-p02] While the determination of responsibility for the accident was complex, the review board concluded that "deficiencies existed in command module design, workmanship and quality control".
[src:aaron-c-waters/apollo-program-p02] At the insistence of NASA Administrator Webb, North American removed Harrison Storms as command module program manager.
[src:aaron-c-waters/apollo-program-p02] Webb also reassigned Apollo Spacecraft Program Office (ASPO) Manager Joseph Francis Shea, replacing him with George Low.
[src:aaron-c-waters/apollo-program-p02] To remedy the causes of the fire, changes were made in the Block II spacecraft and operational procedures, the most important of which were use of a nitrogen/oxygen mixture instead of pure oxygen before and during launch, and removal of flammable cabin and space suit materials.
[src:aaron-c-waters/apollo-program-p02] The Block II design already called for replacement of the Block I plug-type hatch cover with a quick-release, outward opening door.
[src:aaron-c-waters/apollo-program-p02] NASA discontinued the crewed Block I program, using the Block I spacecraft only for uncrewed Saturn V flights.
[src:aaron-c-waters/apollo-program-p02] Crew members would also exclusively wear modified, fire-resistant A7L Block II space suits, and would be designated by the Block II titles, regardless of whether a LM was present on the flight or not.
[src:aaron-c-waters/apollo-program-p02] On April 24, 1967, Mueller published an official Apollo mission numbering scheme, using sequential numbers for all flights, crewed or uncrewed.
[src:aaron-c-waters/apollo-program-p02] The sequence would start with Apollo 4 to cover the first three uncrewed flights while retiring the Apollo 1 designation to honor the crew, per their widows' wishes.
[src:aaron-c-waters/apollo-program-p02] In September 1967, Mueller approved a sequence of mission types which had to be accomplished in order to achieve the crewed lunar landing.
[src:aaron-c-waters/apollo-program-p02] Each step had to be accomplished before the next ones could be performed, and it was unknown how many tries of each mission would be necessary; therefore letters were used instead of numbers.
[src:aaron-c-waters/apollo-program-p02] The list of types covered follow-on lunar exploration to include **H** lunar landings, **I** for lunar orbital survey missions, and **J** for extended-stay lunar landings.
[src:aaron-c-waters/apollo-program-p02] The delay in the CSM caused by the fire enabled NASA to catch up on human-rating the LM and Saturn V.
[src:aaron-c-waters/apollo-program-p02] Apollo 4 (AS-501) was the first uncrewed flight of the Saturn V, carrying a Block I CSM on November 9, 1967.
[src:aaron-c-waters/apollo-program-p02] The capability of the command module's heat shield to survive a trans-lunar reentry was demonstrated by using the service module engine to ram it into the atmosphere at higher than the usual Earth-orbital reentry speed.
[src:aaron-c-waters/apollo-program-p02] Apollo 5 (AS-204) was the first uncrewed test flight of the LM in Earth orbit, launched from pad 37 on January 22, 1968, by the Saturn IB that would have been used for Apollo 1.
[src:aaron-c-waters/apollo-program-p02] The LM engines were successfully test-fired and restarted, despite a computer programming error, which cut short the first descent stage firing.
[src:aaron-c-waters/apollo-program-p02] The ascent engine was fired in abort mode, known as a "fire-in-the-hole" test, where it was lit simultaneously with jettison of the descent stage.
[src:aaron-c-waters/apollo-program-p02] Although Grumman wanted a second uncrewed test, George Low decided the next LM flight would be crewed.
[src:aaron-c-waters/apollo-program-p02] This was followed on April 4, 1968, by Apollo 6 (AS-502) which carried a CSM and a LM Test Article as ballast.
[src:aaron-c-waters/apollo-program-p02] The intent of this mission was to achieve trans-lunar injection, followed closely by a simulated direct-return abort, using the service module engine to achieve another high-speed reentry.
[src:aaron-c-waters/apollo-program-p02] The Saturn V experienced pogo oscillation, a problem caused by non-steady engine combustion, which damaged fuel lines in the second and third stages.
[src:aaron-c-waters/apollo-program-p02] Two S-II engines shut down prematurely, but the remaining engines were able to compensate.
[src:aaron-c-waters/apollo-program-p02] The damage to the third stage engine was more severe, preventing it from restarting for trans-lunar injection.
[src:aaron-c-waters/apollo-program-p02] Mission controllers were able to use the service module engine to essentially repeat the flight profile of Apollo 4.
[src:aaron-c-waters/apollo-program-p02] Based on the good performance of Apollo 6 and identification of satisfactory fixes to the Apollo 6 problems, NASA declared the Saturn V ready to fly crew, canceling a third uncrewed test.
[src:aaron-c-waters/apollo-program-p02] Apollo 7, launched from LC-34 on October 11, 1968, was the C mission, crewed by Schirra, Eisele, and Cunningham.
[src:aaron-c-waters/apollo-program-p02] It was an 11-day Earth-orbital flight which tested the CSM systems.
[src:aaron-c-waters/apollo-program-p02] Apollo 8 was planned to be the D mission in December 1968, crewed by McDivitt, Scott and Schweickart, launched on a Saturn V instead of two Saturn IBs.
[src:aaron-c-waters/apollo-program-p02] In the summer it had become clear that the LM would not be ready in time.
[src:aaron-c-waters/apollo-program-p02] Rather than waste the Saturn V on another simple Earth-orbiting mission, ASPO Manager George Low suggested the bold step of sending Apollo 8 to orbit the Moon instead, deferring the D mission to the next mission in March 1969, and eliminating the E mission.
[src:aaron-c-waters/apollo-program-p02] The Soviet Union had sent two tortoises, mealworms, wine flies, and other lifeforms around the Moon on September 15, 1968, aboard Zond 5, and it was believed they might soon repeat the feat with human cosmonauts.
[src:aaron-c-waters/apollo-program-p02] The decision was not announced publicly until completion of Apollo 7.
[src:aaron-c-waters/apollo-program-p02] Gemini veterans Frank Borman and Jim Lovell, and rookie William Anders captured the world's attention by making ten lunar orbits in 20 hours, transmitting television pictures of the lunar surface on Christmas Eve, and returning safely to Earth.
[src:aaron-c-waters/apollo-program-p02] The following March, LM flight, rendezvous and docking were demonstrated in Earth orbit on Apollo 9, and Schweickart tested the full lunar EVA suit with its portable life support system (PLSS) outside the LM.
[src:aaron-c-waters/apollo-program-p02] The F mission was carried out on Apollo 10 in May 1969 by Gemini veterans Thomas P.
[src:aaron-c-waters/apollo-program-p02] Stafford and Cernan took the LM to within 50,000 feet (15 km) of the lunar surface.
[src:aaron-c-waters/apollo-program-p02] The G mission was achieved on Apollo 11 in July 1969 by an all-Gemini veteran crew consisting of Neil Armstrong, Michael Collins and Buzz Aldrin.
[src:aaron-c-waters/apollo-program-p02] Armstrong and Aldrin performed the first landing at the Sea of Tranquility at 20:17:40 UTC on July 20, 1969.
[src:aaron-c-waters/apollo-program-p02] The astronauts returned safely on July 24.
[src:aaron-c-waters/apollo-program-p02] Bean made a precision landing of Apollo 12 within walking distance of the Surveyor 3 uncrewed lunar probe, which had landed in April 1967 on the Ocean of Storms.
[src:aaron-c-waters/apollo-program-p02] The command module pilot was Gemini veteran Richard F.
[src:aaron-c-waters/apollo-program-p02] Conrad and Bean carried the first lunar surface color television camera, but it was damaged when accidentally pointed into the Sun.
[src:aaron-c-waters/apollo-program-p02] They made two EVAs totaling 7 hours and 45 minutes.
[src:aaron-c-waters/apollo-program-p02] On one, they walked to the Surveyor, photographed it, and removed some parts which they returned to Earth.
[src:aaron-c-waters/apollo-program-p02] The contracted batch of 15 Saturn Vs was enough for lunar landing missions through Apollo 20.
[src:aaron-c-waters/apollo-program-p02] Shortly after Apollo 11, NASA publicized a preliminary list of eight more planned landing sites after Apollo 12, with plans to increase the mass of the CSM and LM for the last five missions, along with the payload capacity of the Saturn V.
[src:aaron-c-waters/apollo-program-p02] These final missions would combine the I and J types in the 1967 list, allowing the CMP to operate a package of lunar orbital sensors and cameras while his companions were on the surface, and allowing them to stay on the Moon for over three days.
[src:aaron-c-waters/apollo-program-p02] These missions would also carry the Lunar Roving Vehicle (LRV) increasing the exploration area and allowing televised liftoff of the LM.
[src:aaron-c-waters/apollo-program-p02] Also, the Block II spacesuit was revised for the extended missions to allow greater flexibility and visibility for driving the LRV.
[src:aaron-c-waters/apollo-program-p02] The success of the first two landings allowed the remaining missions to be crewed with a single veteran as commander, with two rookies.
[src:aaron-c-waters/apollo-program-p02] Apollo 13 launched Lovell, Jack Swigert, and Fred Haise in April 1970, headed for the Fra Mauro formation.
[src:aaron-c-waters/apollo-program-p02] But two days out, a liquid oxygen tank exploded, disabling the service module and forcing the crew to use the LM as a "lifeboat" to return to Earth.
[src:aaron-c-waters/apollo-program-p02] Another NASA review board was convened to determine the cause, which turned out to be a combination of damage of the tank in the factory, and a subcontractor not making a tank component according to updated design specifications.
[src:aaron-c-waters/apollo-program-p02] Apollo was grounded again, for the remainder of 1970 while the oxygen tank was redesigned and an extra one was added.
[src:aaron-c-waters/apollo-program-p02] About the time of the first landing in 1969, it was decided to use an existing Saturn V to launch the Skylab orbital laboratory pre-built on the ground, replacing the original plan to construct it in orbit from several Saturn IB launches; this eliminated Apollo 20.
[src:aaron-c-waters/apollo-program-p02] NASA's yearly budget also began to shrink in light of the landing, and NASA also had to make funds available for the development of the upcoming Space Shuttle.
[src:aaron-c-waters/apollo-program-p02] By 1971, the decision was made to also cancel missions 18 and 19.
[src:aaron-c-waters/apollo-program-p02] The two unused Saturn Vs became museum exhibits at the John F.
[src:aaron-c-waters/apollo-program-p02] Kennedy Space Center on Merritt Island, Florida, George C.
[src:aaron-c-waters/apollo-program-p02] Marshall Space Center in Huntsville, Alabama, Michoud Assembly Facility in New Orleans, Louisiana, and Lyndon B.
[src:aaron-c-waters/apollo-program-p02] The cutbacks forced mission planners to reassess the original planned landing sites in order to achieve the most effective geological sample and data collection from the remaining four missions.
[src:aaron-c-waters/apollo-program-p02] Apollo 15 had been planned to be the last of the H series missions, but since there would be only two subsequent missions left, it was changed to the first of three J missions.
[src:aaron-c-waters/apollo-program-p02] Apollo 13's Fra Mauro mission was reassigned to Apollo 14, commanded in February 1971 by Mercury veteran Alan Shepard, with Stuart Roosa and Edgar Mitchell.
[src:aaron-c-waters/apollo-program-p02] Shepard and Mitchell spent 33 hours and 31 minutes on the surface, and completed two EVAs totalling 9 hours 24 minutes, which was a record for the longest EVA by a lunar crew at the time.
[src:aaron-c-waters/apollo-program-p02] In August 1971, just after conclusion of the Apollo 15 mission, President Richard Nixon proposed canceling the two remaining lunar landing missions, Apollo 16 and 17.
[src:aaron-c-waters/apollo-program-p02] Office of Management and Budget Deputy Director Caspar Weinberger was opposed to this, and persuaded Nixon to keep the remaining missions.
[src:aaron-c-waters/apollo-program-p02] Apollo 15 was launched on July 26, 1971, with David Scott, Alfred Worden and James Irwin.
[src:aaron-c-waters/apollo-program-p02] Scott and Irwin landed on July 30 near Hadley Rille, and spent just under two days, 19 hours on the surface.
[src:aaron-c-waters/apollo-program-p02] In over 18 hours of EVA, they collected about 77 kilograms (170 lb) of lunar material.
[src:aaron-c-waters/apollo-program-p02] Apollo 16 landed in the Descartes Highlands on April 20, 1972.
[src:aaron-c-waters/apollo-program-p02] The crew was commanded by John Young, with Ken Mattingly and Charles Duke.
[src:aaron-c-waters/apollo-program-p02] Young and Duke spent just under three days on the surface, with a total of over 20 hours EVA.
[src:aaron-c-waters/apollo-program-p02] Apollo 17 was the last of the Apollo program, landing in the Taurus–Littrow region in December 1972.
[src:aaron-c-waters/apollo-program-p02] Evans and NASA's first scientist-astronaut, geologist Harrison H.
[src:aaron-c-waters/apollo-program-p02] Schmitt was originally scheduled for Apollo 18, but the lunar geological community lobbied for his inclusion on the final lunar landing.
[src:aaron-c-waters/apollo-program-p02] Cernan and Schmitt stayed on the surface for just over three days and spent just over 23 hours of total EVA.
[src:aaron-c-waters/apollo-program-p02] Several missions were planned for but were canceled before details were finalized.
[src:aaron-c-waters/apollo-program-p02] Source: *Apollo by the Numbers: A Statistical Reference* (Orloff 2004).
[src:aaron-c-waters/apollo-program-p02] The Apollo program returned over 382 kg (842 lb) of lunar rocks and soil to the Lunar Receiving Laboratory in Houston.
[src:aaron-c-waters/apollo-program-p02] Today, 75% of the samples are stored at the Lunar Sample Laboratory Facility built in 1979.
[src:aaron-c-waters/apollo-program-p02] The rocks collected from the Moon are extremely old compared to rocks found on Earth, as measured by radiometric dating techniques.
[src:aaron-c-waters/apollo-program-p02] They range in age from about 3.2 billion years for the basaltic samples derived from the lunar maria, to about 4.6 billion years for samples derived from the highlands crust.
[src:aaron-c-waters/apollo-program-p02] As such, they represent samples from a very early period in the development of the Solar System, that are largely absent on Earth.
[src:aaron-c-waters/apollo-program-p02] One important rock found during the Apollo Program is dubbed the Genesis Rock, retrieved by astronauts David Scott and James Irwin during the Apollo 15 mission.
[src:aaron-c-waters/apollo-program-p02] This anorthosite rock is composed almost exclusively of the calcium-rich feldspar mineral anorthite, and is believed to be representative of the highland crust.
[src:aaron-c-waters/apollo-program-p02] A geochemical component called KREEP was discovered by Apollo 12, which has no known terrestrial counterpart.
[src:aaron-c-waters/apollo-program-p02] KREEP and the anorthositic samples have been used to infer that the outer portion of the Moon was once completely molten (see lunar magma ocean).
[src:aaron-c-waters/apollo-program-p02] Almost all the rocks show evidence of impact process effects.
[src:aaron-c-waters/apollo-program-p02] Many samples appear to be pitted with micrometeoroid impact craters, which is never seen on Earth rocks, due to the thick atmosphere.
[src:aaron-c-waters/apollo-program-p02] Many show signs of being subjected to high-pressure shock waves that are generated during impact events.
[src:aaron-c-waters/apollo-program-p02] Some of the returned samples are of *impact melt* (materials melted near an impact crater.) All samples returned from the Moon are highly brecciated as a result of being subjected to multiple impact events.
[src:aaron-c-waters/apollo-program-p02] From analyses of the composition of the returned lunar samples, it is now believed that the Moon was created through the impact of a large astronomical body with Earth.
[src:aaron-c-waters/apollo-program-p02] Apollo cost $25.4 billion or approximately $257 billion (2023) using improved cost analysis.
[src:aaron-c-waters/apollo-program-p02] Of this amount, $20.2 billion ($149 billion adjusted) was spent on the design, development, and production of the Saturn family of launch vehicles, the Apollo spacecraft, spacesuits, scientific experiments, and mission operations.
[src:aaron-c-waters/apollo-program-p02] The cost of constructing and operating Apollo-related ground facilities, such as the NASA human spaceflight centers and the global tracking and data acquisition network, added an additional $5.2 billion ($38.3 billion adjusted).
[src:aaron-c-waters/apollo-program-p02] The amount grows to $28 billion ($280 billion adjusted) if the costs for related projects such as Project Gemini and the robotic Ranger, Surveyor, and Lunar Orbiter programs are included.
[src:aaron-c-waters/apollo-program-p02] Accurate estimates of human spaceflight costs were difficult in the early 1960s, as the capability was new and management experience was lacking.
[src:aaron-c-waters/apollo-program-p02] Preliminary cost analysis by NASA estimated $7 billion – $12 billion for a crewed lunar landing effort.
[src:aaron-c-waters/apollo-program-p02] NASA Administrator James Webb increased this estimate to $20 billion before reporting it to Vice President Johnson in April 1961.
[src:aaron-c-waters/apollo-program-p02] Project Apollo was a massive undertaking, representing the largest research and development project in peacetime.
[src:aaron-c-waters/apollo-program-p02] At its peak, it employed over 400,000 employees and contractors around the country and accounted for more than half of NASA's total spending in the 1960s.
[src:aaron-c-waters/apollo-program-p02] After the first Moon landing, public and political interest waned, including that of President Nixon, who wanted to rein in federal spending.
[src:aaron-c-waters/apollo-program-p02] NASA's budget could not sustain Apollo missions which cost, on average, $445 million ($2.73 billion adjusted) each while simultaneously developing the Space Shuttle.
[src:aaron-c-waters/apollo-program-p02] The final fiscal year of Apollo funding was 1973.
[src:aaron-c-waters/apollo-program-p02] Looking beyond the crewed lunar landings, NASA investigated several post-lunar applications for Apollo hardware.
[src:aaron-c-waters/apollo-program-p02] The Apollo Extension Series (*Apollo X*) proposed up to 30 flights to Earth orbit, using the space in the Spacecraft Lunar Module Adapter (SLA) to house a small orbital laboratory (workshop).
[src:aaron-c-waters/apollo-program-p02] Astronauts would continue to use the CSM as a ferry to the station.
[src:aaron-c-waters/apollo-program-p02] This study was followed by design of a larger orbital workshop to be built in orbit from an empty S-IVB Saturn upper stage and grew into the Apollo Applications Program (AAP).
[src:aaron-c-waters/apollo-program-p02] The workshop was to be supplemented by the Apollo Telescope Mount, which could be attached to the ascent stage of the lunar module via a rack.
[src:aaron-c-waters/apollo-program-p02] The most ambitious plan called for using an empty S-IVB as an interplanetary spacecraft for a Venus fly-by mission.
[src:aaron-c-waters/apollo-program-p02] The S-IVB orbital workshop was the only one of these plans to make it off the drawing board.
[src:aaron-c-waters/apollo-program-p02] Dubbed Skylab, it was assembled on the ground rather than in space, and launched in 1973 using the two lower stages of a Saturn V.
[src:aaron-c-waters/apollo-program-p02] It was equipped with an Apollo Telescope Mount.
[src:aaron-c-waters/apollo-program-p02] Skylab's last crew departed the station on February 8, 1974, and the station itself re-entered the atmosphere in 1979 after development of the Space Shuttle was delayed too long to save it.
[src:aaron-c-waters/apollo-program-p02] The Apollo–Soyuz program also used Apollo hardware for the first joint nation spaceflight, paving the way for future cooperation with other nations in the Space Shuttle and International Space Station programs.
[src:aaron-c-waters/apollo-program-p02] In 2008, Japan Aerospace Exploration Agency's SELENE probe observed evidence of the halo surrounding the Apollo 15 Lunar Module blast crater while orbiting above the lunar surface.
[src:aaron-c-waters/apollo-program-p02] Beginning in 2009, NASA's robotic Lunar Reconnaissance Orbiter, while orbiting 50 kilometers (31 mi) above the Moon, photographed the remnants of the Apollo program left on the lunar surface, and each site where crewed Apollo flights landed.
[src:aaron-c-waters/apollo-program-p02] The flags cannot be seen through a telescope from Earth.
[src:aaron-c-waters/apollo-program-p02] The Apollo program has been described as the greatest technological achievement in human history.
[src:aaron-c-waters/apollo-program-p02] Apollo stimulated many areas of technology, leading to over 1,800 spinoff products as of 2015, including advances in the development of cordless power tools, fireproof materials, heart monitors, solar panels, digital imaging, and the use of liquid methane as fuel.
[src:aaron-c-waters/apollo-program-p02] The flight computer design used in both the lunar and command modules was, along with the Polaris and Minuteman missile systems, the driving force behind early research into integrated circuits (ICs).
[src:aaron-c-waters/apollo-program-p02] By 1963, Apollo was using 60 percent of the United States' production of ICs.
[src:aaron-c-waters/apollo-program-p02] The crucial difference between the requirements of Apollo and the missile programs was Apollo's much greater need for reliability.
[src:aaron-c-waters/apollo-program-p02] While the Navy and Air Force could work around reliability problems by deploying more missiles, the political and financial cost of failure of an Apollo mission was unacceptably high.
[src:aaron-c-waters/apollo-program-p02] Technologies and techniques required for Apollo were developed by Project Gemini.
[src:aaron-c-waters/apollo-program-p02] The Apollo project was enabled by NASA's adoption of new advances in semiconductor electronic technology, including metal–oxide–semiconductor field-effect transistors (MOSFETs) in the Interplanetary Monitoring Platform (IMP) and silicon integrated circuit chips in the Apollo Guidance Computer (AGC).
[src:aaron-c-waters/apollo-program-p02] The crew of Apollo 8 sent the first live televised pictures of the Earth and the Moon back to Earth, and read from the creation story in the Book of Genesis, on Christmas Eve 1968.
[src:aaron-c-waters/apollo-program-p02] An estimated one-quarter of the population of the world saw—either live or delayed—the Christmas Eve transmission during the ninth orbit of the Moon, and an estimated one-fifth of the population of the world watched the live transmission of the Apollo 11 moonwalk.
[src:aaron-c-waters/apollo-program-p02] The Apollo program also affected environmental activism in the 1970s due to photos taken by the astronauts.
[src:aaron-c-waters/apollo-program-p02] The most well known include *Earthrise*, taken by William Anders on Apollo 8, and *The Blue Marble*, taken by the Apollo 17 astronauts.
[src:aaron-c-waters/apollo-program-p02] *The Blue Marble* was released during a surge in environmentalism, and became a symbol of the environmental movement as a depiction of Earth's frailty, vulnerability, and isolation amid the vast expanse of space.
[src:aaron-c-waters/apollo-program-p02] According to *The Economist*, Apollo succeeded in accomplishing President Kennedy's goal of taking on the Soviet Union in the Space Race by accomplishing a singular and significant achievement, to demonstrate the superiority of the free-market system.
[src:aaron-c-waters/apollo-program-p02] The publication noted the irony that in order to achieve the goal, the program required the organization of tremendous public resources within a vast, centralized government bureaucracy.
[src:aaron-c-waters/apollo-program-p02] Prior to Apollo 11's 40th anniversary in 2009, NASA searched for the original videotapes of the mission's live televised moonwalk.
[src:aaron-c-waters/apollo-program-p02] After an exhaustive three-year search, it was concluded that the tapes had probably been erased and reused.
[src:aaron-c-waters/apollo-program-p02] A new digitally remastered version of the best available broadcast television footage was released instead.
[src:aaron-c-waters/attack-on-pearl-harbor-p01] On December 7, 1941, the Empire of Japan launched a surprise military strike on the United States Pacific Fleet at its naval base at Pearl Harbor on Oahu, Hawaii Territory.
[src:aaron-c-waters/attack-on-pearl-harbor-p01] At the time, the US was a neutral country in World War II.
[src:aaron-c-waters/attack-on-pearl-harbor-p01] The air raid on Pearl Harbor, which was launched from aircraft carriers, prompted the US to declare war on Japan the next day.
[src:aaron-c-waters/attack-on-pearl-harbor-p01] The Japanese military leadership referred to the attack as the **Hawaii Operation** and **Operation AI**, and as **Operation Z** during its planning.
[src:aaron-c-waters/attack-on-pearl-harbor-p01] The attack on Pearl Harbor was preceded by months of negotiations between the US and Japan over the future of the Pacific.
[src:aaron-c-waters/attack-on-pearl-harbor-p01] Japanese demands included that the US end its sanctions against Japan, cease aiding China in the Second Sino-Japanese War, and allow Japan access to the resources of the Dutch East Indies.
[src:aaron-c-waters/attack-on-pearl-harbor-p01] Japan dispatched its naval attack group on November 26, 1941, just before receiving the Hull note, which stated the US desire that Japan withdraw from China and French Indochina.
[src:aaron-c-waters/attack-on-pearl-harbor-p01] Isoroku Yamamoto, commander of the Japanese Combined Fleet, planned the attack as a pre-emptive strike on the Pacific Fleet, which had been based at Pearl Harbor since 1940 in order to prevent it from interfering with Japan's planned actions in Southeast Asia.
[src:aaron-c-waters/attack-on-pearl-harbor-p01] Yamamoto hoped that the strike would enable Japan to make rapid territorial gains and negotiate peace.
[src:aaron-c-waters/attack-on-pearl-harbor-p01] In addition to Pearl Harbor, over seven hours Japan launched coordinated attacks on the US-held Philippines, Guam, and Wake Island, as well as on the British Empire in Malaya, Singapore, and Hong Kong.
[src:aaron-c-waters/attack-on-pearl-harbor-p01] The attacking force, commanded by Chūichi Nagumo, launched its attack at 7:48 a.m.
[src:aaron-c-waters/attack-on-pearl-harbor-p01] The base was struck by 353 fighters, level and dive bombers, and torpedo bombers in two waves launched from six aircraft carriers.
[src:aaron-c-waters/attack-on-pearl-harbor-p01] Of the eight US battleships present, all were damaged and four were sunk.
[src:aaron-c-waters/attack-on-pearl-harbor-p01] All but the USS *Arizona* and the USS *Utah* were later refloated, and six were returned to service during the war.
[src:aaron-c-waters/attack-on-pearl-harbor-p01] The Japanese also sank or damaged three cruisers, three destroyers, an anti-aircraft training ship, and a minelayer.
[src:aaron-c-waters/attack-on-pearl-harbor-p01] More than 180 US aircraft were destroyed.
[src:aaron-c-waters/attack-on-pearl-harbor-p01] A total of 2,403 Americans were killed and 1,178 others were wounded.
[src:aaron-c-waters/attack-on-pearl-harbor-p01] Japanese losses totaled 29 aircraft, five midget submarines, and 130 personnel.
[src:aaron-c-waters/attack-on-pearl-harbor-p01] The three US carriers assigned to Pearl Harbor were at sea at the time, and important base installations, including its oil storage and naval repair facilities, were not attacked.
[src:aaron-c-waters/attack-on-pearl-harbor-p01] Japan declared war on the US and the British Empire later that day (December 8 in Tokyo), but the declarations were not delivered until the next day.
[src:aaron-c-waters/attack-on-pearl-harbor-p01] On December 8, both the United Kingdom and the US declared war on Japan.
[src:aaron-c-waters/attack-on-pearl-harbor-p01] On December 11, though they had no formal obligation to do so under the Tripartite Pact with Japan, Germany and Italy each declared war on the United States, which responded by declaring war on Germany and Italy.
[src:aaron-c-waters/attack-on-pearl-harbor-p01] While there were historical precedents for unannounced military action by Japan, the lack of a formal warning and perception that the attack had been unprovoked led US President Franklin D.
[src:aaron-c-waters/attack-on-pearl-harbor-p01] Roosevelt to famously label December 7, 1941, "a date which will live in infamy".
[src:aaron-c-waters/attack-on-pearl-harbor-p01] The attack remains the deadliest event to ever happen in Hawaii, and for nearly 60 years, was the deadliest foreign attack on the US until the September 11 attacks in 2001.
[src:aaron-c-waters/attack-on-pearl-harbor-p01] War between the Empire of Japan and the United States was seen as a possibility since the 1920s.
[src:aaron-c-waters/attack-on-pearl-harbor-p01] Japan had been wary of American territorial and military expansion in the Pacific and Asia since the late 1890s, followed by the annexation of islands, such as Hawaii and the Philippines, which were close to or within Japan's perceived sphere of influence.
[src:aaron-c-waters/attack-on-pearl-harbor-p01] At the same time, Japanese strategic thinkers believed that Japan needed economic self-sufficiency in order to wage modern war.
[src:aaron-c-waters/attack-on-pearl-harbor-p01] The experiences of World War I had taught the Japanese that modern wars would be protracted, require total mobilization, and create vulnerabilities for trade embargoes and encirclement.
[src:aaron-c-waters/attack-on-pearl-harbor-p01] As a consequence, Japan needed access to strategically important resources (e.g., iron, oil) that could not be extracted at sufficient levels in the home islands.
[src:aaron-c-waters/attack-on-pearl-harbor-p01] Although Japan had begun to take a hostile stance against the United States after the rejection of the Racial Equality Proposal, their relationship was cordial enough to remain trading partners.
[src:aaron-c-waters/attack-on-pearl-harbor-p01] Tensions did not seriously grow until Japan's invasion of Manchuria in 1931.
[src:aaron-c-waters/attack-on-pearl-harbor-p01] Over the next decade, Japan expanded into China, leading to the Second Sino-Japanese War in 1937.
[src:aaron-c-waters/attack-on-pearl-harbor-p01] Japan spent considerable effort trying to isolate China and endeavored to secure enough independent resources to attain victory on the mainland.
[src:aaron-c-waters/attack-on-pearl-harbor-p01] The "Southern Operation" was designed to assist these efforts.
[src:aaron-c-waters/attack-on-pearl-harbor-p01] Nevertheless, Japan would still rely heavily on US oil imports, including to Japanese forces in Japan-occupied Manchuria.
[src:aaron-c-waters/attack-on-pearl-harbor-p01] In a memorandum dated October 24, 1934, Chief of the Division of Far Eastern Affairs Stanley K.
[src:aaron-c-waters/attack-on-pearl-harbor-p01] Hornbeck discussed his meeting with Standard Oil New Jersey head Walter C.
[src:aaron-c-waters/attack-on-pearl-harbor-p01] The memo described that Teagle was uncooperative with US recommendations and how Standard Oil was given special treatment by the Japanese government, which made the company less subject to Japan's national business regulation policies than other companies.
[src:aaron-c-waters/attack-on-pearl-harbor-p01] Starting in December 1937, events such as the Japanese attack on USS *Panay*, the Allison incident, and the Rape of Nanjing swung Western public opinion sharply against Japan.
[src:aaron-c-waters/attack-on-pearl-harbor-p01] The United States unsuccessfully proposed a joint action with the United Kingdom to blockade Japan.
[src:aaron-c-waters/attack-on-pearl-harbor-p01] In 1938, following an appeal by President Roosevelt, American companies stopped providing Japan with implements of war.
[src:aaron-c-waters/attack-on-pearl-harbor-p01] In 1940, Japan invaded French Indochina, attempting to stymie the flow of supplies reaching China.
[src:aaron-c-waters/attack-on-pearl-harbor-p01] The United States halted shipments of airplanes, parts, machine tools, and aviation gasoline to Japan, which Japan perceived as an unfriendly act.
[src:aaron-c-waters/attack-on-pearl-harbor-p01] The United States did not stop oil exports, however, partly because of the prevailing sentiment in Washington that given Japanese dependence on American oil, such an action was likely to be considered an extreme provocation.
[src:aaron-c-waters/attack-on-pearl-harbor-p01] Roosevelt moved the Pacific Fleet from San Diego to Hawaii.
[src:aaron-c-waters/attack-on-pearl-harbor-p01] He also ordered a military buildup in the Philippines, taking both actions in the hope of discouraging Japanese aggression in the Far East.
[src:aaron-c-waters/attack-on-pearl-harbor-p01] Because the Japanese high command was mistakenly certain any attack on the United Kingdom's Southeast Asian colonies, including Singapore, would bring the United States into the war, a devastating preventive strike appeared to be the only way to prevent American naval interference.
[src:aaron-c-waters/attack-on-pearl-harbor-p01] An invasion of the Philippines was also considered necessary by Japanese war planners.
[src:aaron-c-waters/attack-on-pearl-harbor-p01] The American War Plan Orange had envisioned defending the Philippines with an elite force of 40,000 men; this option was never implemented due to opposition from Douglas MacArthur, who felt he would need a force ten times that size.
[src:aaron-c-waters/attack-on-pearl-harbor-p01] By 1941, American planners expected to have to abandon the Philippines at the outbreak of war.
[src:aaron-c-waters/attack-on-pearl-harbor-p01] Hart, commander of the United States Asiatic Fleet, was given orders to that effect.
[src:aaron-c-waters/attack-on-pearl-harbor-p01] The United States finally ceased oil exports to Japan in July 1941, following the seizure of French Indochina after the Fall of France, in part because of new American restrictions on domestic oil consumption.
[src:aaron-c-waters/attack-on-pearl-harbor-p01] Because of this decision, Japan proceeded with plans to take the oil-rich Dutch East Indies.
[src:aaron-c-waters/attack-on-pearl-harbor-p01] On August 17, Roosevelt warned Japan that America was prepared to take opposing steps if "neighboring countries" were attacked.
[src:aaron-c-waters/attack-on-pearl-harbor-p01] Japan and the United States engaged in negotiations during 1941, attempting to improve relations.
[src:aaron-c-waters/attack-on-pearl-harbor-p01] In the course of these negotiations, Japan offered to withdraw from most of China and Indochina after making peace with the Nationalist government.
[src:aaron-c-waters/attack-on-pearl-harbor-p01] It also proposed to adopt an independent interpretation of the Tripartite Pact and to refrain from trade discrimination, provided all other nations reciprocated.
[src:aaron-c-waters/attack-on-pearl-harbor-p01] Japanese Prime Minister Konoe then offered to meet with Roosevelt, but Roosevelt insisted on reaching an agreement before any meeting.
[src:aaron-c-waters/attack-on-pearl-harbor-p01] The American ambassador to Japan repeatedly urged Roosevelt to accept the meeting, warning that it was the only way to preserve the conciliatory Konoe government and peace in the Pacific.
[src:aaron-c-waters/attack-on-pearl-harbor-p01] However, his recommendation was not acted upon.
[src:aaron-c-waters/attack-on-pearl-harbor-p01] The Konoe government collapsed the following month when the Japanese military rejected a withdrawal of all troops from China.
[src:aaron-c-waters/attack-on-pearl-harbor-p01] The American counter-proposal of November 26 (November 27 in Japan), the Hull note, required Japan to completely evacuate China without conditions and conclude non-aggression pacts with Pacific powers.
[src:aaron-c-waters/attack-on-pearl-harbor-p01] On November 26 in Japan, the day before the note's delivery, the Japanese task force left port for Pearl Harbor.
[src:aaron-c-waters/attack-on-pearl-harbor-p01] The Japanese intended the attack as a preventive action to keep the United States Pacific Fleet from interfering with their planned military actions in Southeast Asia against overseas territories of the United Kingdom, the Netherlands, and the United States.
[src:aaron-c-waters/attack-on-pearl-harbor-p01] Over the course of seven hours, there were coordinated Japanese attacks on the American-held Philippines, Guam, Wake Island, Midway Atoll and on the British Empire in Malaya, Singapore, and Hong Kong.
[src:aaron-c-waters/attack-on-pearl-harbor-p01] Preliminary planning for an attack on Pearl Harbor to protect the move into the "Southern Resource Area", the Japanese term for the Dutch East Indies and Southeast Asia generally, began early in 1941 under the auspices of Admiral Isoroku Yamamoto, then commanding Japan's Combined Fleet.
[src:aaron-c-waters/attack-on-pearl-harbor-p01] He won assent to formal planning and training for an attack from the Imperial Japanese Navy General Staff only after much contention with Naval Headquarters, including a threat to resign his command.
[src:aaron-c-waters/attack-on-pearl-harbor-p01] Full-scale planning was underway by early spring 1941, primarily by Rear Admiral Ryūnosuke Kusaka, with assistance from Commander Minoru Genda and Yamamoto's Deputy Chief of Staff, Captain Kameto Kuroshima.
[src:aaron-c-waters/attack-on-pearl-harbor-p01] The planners studied the 1940 British air attack on the Italian fleet at Taranto intensively.
[src:aaron-c-waters/attack-on-pearl-harbor-p01] Over the next several months, pilots were trained, equipment was adapted, and intelligence was collected.
[src:aaron-c-waters/attack-on-pearl-harbor-p01] Despite these preparations, Emperor Hirohito did not approve the attack plan until November 5, after the third of four Imperial Conferences called to consider the matter.
[src:aaron-c-waters/attack-on-pearl-harbor-p01] At first, he hesitated to engage in war but eventually authorized the Pearl Harbor strike despite dissent from certain advisors.
[src:aaron-c-waters/attack-on-pearl-harbor-p01] Final authorization was not given by the emperor until December 1, after a majority of Japanese leaders advised him the Hull note would "destroy the fruits of the China incident, endanger Manchukuo and undermine Japanese control of Korea".
[src:aaron-c-waters/attack-on-pearl-harbor-p01] Before the attack, he became more involved in military matters, even joining the Conference of Military Councillors, which was considered unusual for him.
[src:aaron-c-waters/attack-on-pearl-harbor-p01] Additionally, he actively sought more information about the war plans.
[src:aaron-c-waters/attack-on-pearl-harbor-p01] According to an aide, he openly displayed happiness upon hearing about the success of the surprise attacks.
[src:aaron-c-waters/attack-on-pearl-harbor-p01] By late 1941, many observers believed that hostilities between the United States and Japan were imminent.
[src:aaron-c-waters/attack-on-pearl-harbor-p01] A Gallup poll just before the attack on Pearl Harbor found that 52% of Americans expected war with Japan, 27% did not, and 21% had no opinion.
[src:aaron-c-waters/attack-on-pearl-harbor-p01] While American Pacific bases and facilities had been placed on alert on many occasions, officials doubted Pearl Harbor would be the first target; instead, they expected the Philippines to be attacked first.
[src:aaron-c-waters/attack-on-pearl-harbor-p01] This presumption was due to the threat that the air bases throughout that country and the naval base at Manila posed to sea lanes, as well as to the shipment of supplies to Japan from territory to the south.
[src:aaron-c-waters/attack-on-pearl-harbor-p01] They also incorrectly believed that Japan was not capable of mounting more than one major naval operation at a time.
[src:aaron-c-waters/attack-on-pearl-harbor-p01] The Japanese attack had several major aims.
[src:aaron-c-waters/attack-on-pearl-harbor-p01] First, it intended to destroy important American fleet units, thereby preventing the Pacific Fleet from interfering with the Japanese conquest of the Dutch East Indies and Malaya and enabling Japan to conquer Southeast Asia without interference.
[src:aaron-c-waters/attack-on-pearl-harbor-p01] The leaders of the Imperial Japanese Navy (IJN) subscribed to Alfred Thayer Mahan's "decisive battle" doctrine, especially that of destroying the maximum number of battleships.
[src:aaron-c-waters/attack-on-pearl-harbor-p01] Second, it was hoped to buy time for Japan to consolidate its position and increase its naval strength before shipbuilding authorized by the 1940 Vinson-Walsh Act erased any chance of victory.
[src:aaron-c-waters/attack-on-pearl-harbor-p01] Third, to deliver a blow to America's ability to mobilize its forces in the Pacific, battleships were chosen as the main targets, since they were the prestige ships of navies at the time.
[src:aaron-c-waters/attack-on-pearl-harbor-p01] Finally, it was hoped that the attack would undermine American morale to such an extent that the American government would drop its demands contrary to Japanese interests and seek a peace compromise.
[src:aaron-c-waters/attack-on-pearl-harbor-p01] A further disadvantage would prove to be the unexpected absence of all three Pacific Fleet aircraft carriers (*Enterprise*, *Lexington*, and *Saratoga*).
[src:aaron-c-waters/attack-on-pearl-harbor-p01] Despite these concerns, Yamamoto decided to press ahead.
[src:aaron-c-waters/attack-on-pearl-harbor-p01] Japanese confidence in their ability to win a short war meant that other targets in the harbor, especially the navy yard, oil tank farms and submarine base, were left unscathed, since by their thinking the war would be over before the influence of these facilities would be felt.
[src:aaron-c-waters/attack-on-pearl-harbor-p01] The Japanese plan was for the fleet to steam to a position northwest of Hawaii, and attack Pearl Harbor with aircraft.
[src:aaron-c-waters/attack-on-pearl-harbor-p01] The attack would consist of about 360 aircraft in two waves.
[src:aaron-c-waters/attack-on-pearl-harbor-p01] 48 fighter aircraft would remain as defensive combat air patrol (CAP) over the fleet.
[src:aaron-c-waters/attack-on-pearl-harbor-p01] The first wave of 180 aircraft was to be the primary attack.
[src:aaron-c-waters/attack-on-pearl-harbor-p01] The level bombers in this wave were armed with armor-piercing bombs or specially adapted Type 91 aerial torpedoes equipped with an anti-roll mechanism and a rudder extension to operate in the shallow water of Pearl Harbor.
[src:aaron-c-waters/attack-on-pearl-harbor-p01] The level bombers were to attack battleships and aircraft carriers, or if these were not present, cruisers and destroyers.
[src:aaron-c-waters/attack-on-pearl-harbor-p01] The dive bombers were to attack land targets with general purpose (GP) bombs.
[src:aaron-c-waters/attack-on-pearl-harbor-p01] The fighters were to strafe airfields, destroying aircraft on the ground, and engage any that got into the air, thus preventing any interference with the bombers.
[src:aaron-c-waters/attack-on-pearl-harbor-p01] The second wave of 180 aircraft was to be similar, but carry only GP bombs and mainly strike airfields.
[src:aaron-c-waters/attack-on-pearl-harbor-p01] They would target carriers first, cruisers second, and battleships third.
[src:aaron-c-waters/attack-on-pearl-harbor-p01] Returning fighters were to refuel and then join the CAP over the fleet.
[src:aaron-c-waters/attack-on-pearl-harbor-p01] Before launching the attack, the Strike Force would launch two reconnaissance floatplanes from heavy cruisers *Chikuma* and *Tone*, to scout Oahu and Lahaina Roads near Maui, respectively.
[src:aaron-c-waters/attack-on-pearl-harbor-p01] Some historians think these reconnaissance aircraft flights risked alerting the Americans, and were not necessary.
[src:aaron-c-waters/attack-on-pearl-harbor-p01] Fleet composition and preparedness information in Pearl Harbor were already known from the reports of the Japanese spy Takeo Yoshikawa.
[src:aaron-c-waters/attack-on-pearl-harbor-p01] Fleet submarines *I-16*, *I-18*, *I-20*, *I-22*, and *I-24* each embarked a Type A midget submarine for transport to the waters off Oahu.
[src:aaron-c-waters/attack-on-pearl-harbor-p01] The five I-boats left Kure Naval District on November 25, 1941.
[src:aaron-c-waters/attack-on-pearl-harbor-p01] On December 6, they came to within 10 nmi (19 km; 12 mi) of the mouth of Pearl Harbor and launched their midget subs at about 01:00 local time on December 7.
[src:aaron-c-waters/attack-on-pearl-harbor-p01] At 03:42 Hawaiian time, the minesweeper *Condor* spotted a midget submarine periscope southwest of the Pearl Harbor entrance buoy and alerted the destroyer *Ward*.
[src:aaron-c-waters/attack-on-pearl-harbor-p01] The midget may have entered Pearl Harbor.
[src:aaron-c-waters/attack-on-pearl-harbor-p01] However, *Ward* sank another midget submarine at 06:37 in the first American shots in the Pacific Theater.
[src:aaron-c-waters/attack-on-pearl-harbor-p01] A midget submarine on the north side of Ford Island missed the seaplane tender *Curtiss* with her first torpedo and missed the attacking destroyer *Monaghan* with her other one before being sunk by *Monaghan* at 08:43.
[src:aaron-c-waters/attack-on-pearl-harbor-p01] A third midget submarine, *Ha-19*, grounded twice, once outside the harbor entrance and again on the east side of Oahu, where it was captured on December 8.
[src:aaron-c-waters/attack-on-pearl-harbor-p01] Ensign Kazuo Sakamaki swam ashore and was captured by Hawaii National Guard Corporal David Akui, becoming the first Japanese prisoner of war.
[src:aaron-c-waters/attack-on-pearl-harbor-p01] A fourth had been damaged by a depth charge attack and was abandoned by its crew before it could fire its torpedoes.
[src:aaron-c-waters/attack-on-pearl-harbor-p01] It was found outside the harbor in 1960.
[src:aaron-c-waters/attack-on-pearl-harbor-p01] Japanese forces received a radio message from a midget submarine at 00:41 on December 8 claiming to have damaged one or more large warships inside Pearl Harbor.
[src:aaron-c-waters/attack-on-pearl-harbor-p01] In 1992, 2000, and 2001, Hawaii Undersea Research Laboratory's submersibles found the wreck of the fifth midget submarine lying in three parts outside Pearl Harbor.
[src:aaron-c-waters/attack-on-pearl-harbor-p01] The wreck was in the debris field where much surplus American equipment had been dumped after the war, including vehicles and landing craft.
[src:aaron-c-waters/attack-on-pearl-harbor-p01] This correlates with reports of two torpedoes fired at the light cruiser *St.
[src:aaron-c-waters/attack-on-pearl-harbor-p01] Louis* at 10:04 at the entrance of Pearl Harbor, and a possible torpedo fired at destroyer *Helm* at 08:21.
[src:aaron-c-waters/attack-on-pearl-harbor-p01] There is dispute over this official chain of events though.
[src:aaron-c-waters/attack-on-pearl-harbor-p01] Louis* saw was also reportedly a porpoising minesweeping float being towed by the destroyer *Boggs*.
[src:aaron-c-waters/attack-on-pearl-harbor-p01] Admiral Chester Nimitz, in a report to Congress, confirmed that one midget submarine's torpedo (possibly from the other midget submarine that fired torpedoes but failed to hit a target) which was fired but did not explode was recovered in Pearl Harbor and was much larger than the aerial torpedoes.
[src:aaron-c-waters/attack-on-pearl-harbor-p01] The attack took place before any formal declaration of war was made by Japan, but this was not Admiral Yamamoto's intention.
[src:aaron-c-waters/attack-on-pearl-harbor-p01] He originally stipulated that the attack should not commence until thirty minutes after Japan had informed the United States that peace negotiations were at an end.
[src:aaron-c-waters/attack-on-pearl-harbor-p01] However, the attack began before the notice could be delivered.
[src:aaron-c-waters/attack-on-pearl-harbor-p01] Tokyo transmitted the 5000-word notification (commonly called the "14-Part Message") in two blocks to the Japanese Embassy in Washington.
[src:aaron-c-waters/attack-on-pearl-harbor-p01] Transcribing the message took too long for the Japanese ambassador to deliver it at 1:00 p.m.
[src:aaron-c-waters/attack-on-pearl-harbor-p01] Washington time, as ordered, and consequently the message was not presented until more than one hour after the attack had begun — but American code breakers had already deciphered and translated most of the message hours before it was scheduled to be delivered.
[src:aaron-c-waters/attack-on-pearl-harbor-p01] The final part of the message is sometimes described as a declaration of war.
[src:aaron-c-waters/attack-on-pearl-harbor-p01] While it was viewed by a number of senior American government and military officials as a very strong indicator negotiations were likely to be terminated and that war might break out at any moment, it neither declared war nor severed diplomatic relations.
[src:aaron-c-waters/attack-on-pearl-harbor-p01] A declaration of war was printed on the front page of Japan's newspapers in the evening edition of December 8 (late December 7 in the United States), but not delivered to the American government until the day after the attack.
[src:aaron-c-waters/attack-on-pearl-harbor-p01] For decades, conventional wisdom held that Japan attacked without first formally breaking diplomatic relations only because of accidents and bumbling that delayed the delivery of a document hinting at war to Washington.
[src:aaron-c-waters/attack-on-pearl-harbor-p01] In any event, even if the Japanese had decoded and delivered the 14-Part Message before the beginning of the attack, it would not have constituted either a formal break of diplomatic relations or a declaration of war.
[src:aaron-c-waters/attack-on-pearl-harbor-p01] United States naval intelligence officers were alarmed by the unusual timing for delivering the message — 1:00 p.m. on a Sunday, which was 7:30 a.m. in Hawaii — and attempted to alert Pearl Harbor.
[src:aaron-c-waters/attack-on-pearl-harbor-p01] But due to communication problems the warning was not delivered before the attack.
[src:aaron-c-waters/attack-on-pearl-harbor-p01] The first attack wave of 183 airplanes, led by Commander Mitsuo Fuchida, was launched north of Oahu.
[src:aaron-c-waters/attack-on-pearl-harbor-p01] Six airplanes failed to launch due to technical difficulties.
[src:aaron-c-waters/attack-on-pearl-harbor-p01] As the first wave approached Oahu, it was detected by United States Army SCR-270 radar positioned at Opana Point near the island's northern tip.
[src:aaron-c-waters/attack-on-pearl-harbor-p01] This post had been in training mode for months, but was not yet operational.
[src:aaron-c-waters/attack-on-pearl-harbor-p01] The operators, Privates George Elliot Jr. and Joseph Lockard, reported a target to Private Joseph P.
[src:aaron-c-waters/attack-on-pearl-harbor-p01] McDonald, who was stationed at Fort Shafter's Intercept Center near Pearl Harbor Lieutenant Kermit A.
[src:aaron-c-waters/attack-on-pearl-harbor-p01] Tyler, a newly assigned officer at the thinly manned Intercept Center, presumed it was the scheduled arrival of six B-17 bombers from California.
[src:aaron-c-waters/attack-on-pearl-harbor-p01] The Japanese planes were approaching from a direction very close (only a few degrees difference) to that of the bombers, and while the operators had never seen a formation as large on radar, they neglected to tell Tyler of its size.
[src:aaron-c-waters/attack-on-pearl-harbor-p01] Tyler, for security reasons, could not tell the operators of the six B-17s that were due (even though it was widely known).
[src:aaron-c-waters/attack-on-pearl-harbor-p01] As the first wave approached Oahu, they encountered and shot down several small American civilian aircraft.
[src:aaron-c-waters/attack-on-pearl-harbor-p01] At least one of these radioed a somewhat incoherent warning.
[src:aaron-c-waters/attack-on-pearl-harbor-p01] Other warnings from ships off the harbor entrance were still being processed or awaiting confirmation when the Japanese air assault began at 7:48 a.m.
[src:aaron-c-waters/attack-on-pearl-harbor-p01] December 8 Japanese Standard Time, as kept by ships of the *Kido Butai*), with the attack on Kaneohe.
[src:aaron-c-waters/attack-on-pearl-harbor-p01] A total of 353 Japanese planes reached Oahu in two waves.
[src:aaron-c-waters/attack-on-pearl-harbor-p01] The 171 planes in the second wave attacked the Army Air Forces' Bellows Field, near Kaneohe on the windward side of the island, and Ford Island.
[src:aaron-c-waters/attack-on-pearl-harbor-p01] The only aerial opposition came from a handful of P-36 Hawks, P-40 Warhawks and some SBD Dauntless dive bombers from the carrier *Enterprise*.
[src:aaron-c-waters/attack-on-pearl-harbor-p01] In the first-wave attack, about eight of the forty-nine 800‑kg (1760 lb) armor-piercing bombs dropped hit their intended battleship targets.
[src:aaron-c-waters/attack-on-pearl-harbor-p01] At least two of those bombs broke up on impact, another detonated before penetrating an unarmored deck, and one was a dud.
[src:aaron-c-waters/attack-on-pearl-harbor-p01] Thirteen of the forty torpedoes hit battleships, while four hit other ships.
[src:aaron-c-waters/attack-on-pearl-harbor-p01] Men aboard the ships awoke to the sounds of alarms, bombs exploding, and gunfire, prompting them to dress as they ran to General Quarters stations.
[src:aaron-c-waters/attack-on-pearl-harbor-p01] (The famous message "Air raid Pearl Harbor.
[src:aaron-c-waters/attack-on-pearl-harbor-p01] This is not drill." was sent from the headquarters of Patrol Wing Two, the first senior Hawaiian command to respond.) American servicemen were caught unprepared by the attack.
[src:aaron-c-waters/attack-on-pearl-harbor-p01] Ammunition lockers were locked, aircraft parked wingtip to wingtip in the open to prevent sabotage, guns unmanned (none of the Navy's 5"/38s, only a quarter of its machine guns, and only four of 31 Army batteries got in action).
[src:aaron-c-waters/attack-on-pearl-harbor-p01] Despite this low alert status, many American military personnel responded effectively during the attack.
[src:aaron-c-waters/attack-on-pearl-harbor-p01] Ensign Joseph Taussig Jr., aboard *Nevada*, commanded the ship's antiaircraft guns and was severely wounded but remained at his post.
[src:aaron-c-waters/attack-on-pearl-harbor-p01] Thomas commanded *Nevada* in the captain's absence and got her underway until the ship was grounded at 9:10 a.m.
[src:aaron-c-waters/attack-on-pearl-harbor-p01] One of the destroyers, *Aylwin*, got underway with only four officers aboard, all ensigns, none with more than a year's sea duty; she operated at sea for 36 hours before her commanding officer managed to get back aboard.
[src:aaron-c-waters/attack-on-pearl-harbor-p01] Captain Mervyn Bennion, commanding *West Virginia*, led his men until he was cut down by fragments from a bomb which hit *Tennessee*, moored alongside.
[src:aaron-c-waters/attack-on-pearl-harbor-p01] The second planned wave consisted of 171 planes: 54 B5Ns, 81 D3As, and 36 A6Ms, commanded by Lieutenant-Commander Shigekazu Shimazaki.
[src:aaron-c-waters/attack-on-pearl-harbor-p01] Four planes failed to launch because of technical difficulties.
[src:aaron-c-waters/attack-on-pearl-harbor-p01] The second wave was divided into three groups.
[src:aaron-c-waters/attack-on-pearl-harbor-p01] One was tasked to attack Kāneʻohe, the rest Pearl Harbor proper.
[src:aaron-c-waters/attack-on-pearl-harbor-p01] The separate sections arrived at the attack point almost simultaneously from several directions.
[src:aaron-c-waters/attack-on-pearl-harbor-p01] was sunk by six torpedoes and two bombs during the attack.
[src:aaron-c-waters/attack-on-pearl-harbor-p01] Ninety minutes after it began, the attack was over.
[src:aaron-c-waters/attack-on-pearl-harbor-p01] 2,008 sailors were killed and 710 others wounded; 218 soldiers and airmen (who were part of the Army before the independent United States Air Force in 1947) were killed and 364 wounded; 109 Marines were killed and 69 wounded; and 68 civilians were killed and 35 wounded.
[src:aaron-c-waters/attack-on-pearl-harbor-p01] In total, 2,403 Americans were killed, and 1,178 were wounded.
[src:aaron-c-waters/attack-on-pearl-harbor-p01] Eighteen ships were sunk or run aground, including five battleships.
[src:aaron-c-waters/attack-on-pearl-harbor-p01] All of the Americans killed or wounded during the attack were legally non-combatants, given that there was no state of war when the attack occurred.
[src:aaron-c-waters/attack-on-pearl-harbor-p01] Of the American fatalities, nearly half were due to the explosion of *Arizona*'s forward magazine after she was hit by a modified 16-inch (410 mm) shell.
[src:aaron-c-waters/attack-on-pearl-harbor-p01] Author Craig Nelson wrote that the vast majority of the US sailors killed at Pearl Harbor were junior enlisted personnel.
[src:aaron-c-waters/attack-on-pearl-harbor-p01] "The officers of the Navy all lived in houses and the junior people were the ones on the boats, so pretty much all of the people who died in the direct line of the attack were very junior people", Nelson said.
[src:aaron-c-waters/attack-on-pearl-harbor-p01] Among the notable civilian casualties were nine Honolulu Fire Department firefighters who responded to Hickam Field during the bombing in Honolulu, becoming the only fire department members on American soil to be attacked by a foreign power in history.
[src:aaron-c-waters/attack-on-pearl-harbor-p01] Fireman Harry Tuck Lee Pang of Engine 6 was killed near the hangars by machine-gun fire from a Japanese plane.
[src:aaron-c-waters/attack-on-pearl-harbor-p01] Captains Thomas Macy and John Carreira of Engine 4 and Engine 1, respectively, died while battling flames inside the hangar after a Japanese bomb crashed through the roof.
[src:aaron-c-waters/attack-on-pearl-harbor-p01] An additional six firefighters were wounded by Japanese shrapnel.
[src:aaron-c-waters/attack-on-pearl-harbor-p01] This made the nine men the only non-military firefighters to receive such an award in American history.
[src:aaron-c-waters/attack-on-pearl-harbor-p01] Already damaged by a torpedo and on fire amidships, *Nevada* attempted to exit the harbor.
[src:aaron-c-waters/attack-on-pearl-harbor-p01] She was targeted by many Japanese bombers as she got underway and sustained more hits from 250 lb (113 kg) bombs, which started further fires.
[src:aaron-c-waters/attack-on-pearl-harbor-p01] She was deliberately beached to avoid risking blocking the harbor entrance if she sank there.
[src:aaron-c-waters/attack-on-pearl-harbor-p01] *California* was hit by two bombs and two torpedoes.
[src:aaron-c-waters/attack-on-pearl-harbor-p01] The crew might have kept her afloat, but were ordered to abandon ship just as they were raising power for the pumps.
[src:aaron-c-waters/attack-on-pearl-harbor-p01] Burning oil from *Arizona* and *West Virginia* was drifted down toward her and probably made the situation look worse than it was.
[src:aaron-c-waters/attack-on-pearl-harbor-p01] The disarmed target ship *Utah* was holed twice by torpedoes.
[src:aaron-c-waters/attack-on-pearl-harbor-p01] *West Virginia* was hit by seven torpedoes, the seventh tearing away her rudder.
[src:aaron-c-waters/attack-on-pearl-harbor-p01] *Oklahoma* was hit by four torpedoes, the last two above her belt armor, which caused her to capsize.
[src:aaron-c-waters/attack-on-pearl-harbor-p01] *Maryland* was hit by two of the converted 16" shells, but neither caused serious damage.
[src:aaron-c-waters/attack-on-pearl-harbor-p01] Although the Japanese concentrated on battleships (the largest vessels present), they did not ignore other targets.
[src:aaron-c-waters/attack-on-pearl-harbor-p01] The light cruiser *Helena* was torpedoed, and the concussion from the blast capsized the neighboring minelayer *Oglala*.
[src:aaron-c-waters/attack-on-pearl-harbor-p01] Two destroyers in dry dock, *Cassin* and *Downes*, were destroyed when bombs penetrated their fuel bunkers.
[src:aaron-c-waters/attack-on-pearl-harbor-p01] The leaking fuel caught fire; flooding the dry dock in an effort to fight fire made the burning oil rise, and both were burned out.
[src:aaron-c-waters/attack-on-pearl-harbor-p01] *Cassin* slipped from her keel blocks and rolled against *Downes*.
[src:aaron-c-waters/attack-on-pearl-harbor-p01] The light cruiser *Raleigh* was holed by a torpedo.
[src:aaron-c-waters/attack-on-pearl-harbor-p01] The light cruiser *Honolulu* was damaged but remained in service.
[src:aaron-c-waters/attack-on-pearl-harbor-p01] The repair vessel *Vestal*, moored alongside *Arizona*, was heavily damaged and beached.
[src:aaron-c-waters/attack-on-pearl-harbor-p01] The seaplane tender *Curtiss* was also damaged.
[src:aaron-c-waters/attack-on-pearl-harbor-p01] The destroyer *Shaw* was badly damaged when two bombs penetrated her forward magazine.
[src:aaron-c-waters/attack-on-pearl-harbor-p01] Of the 402 American aircraft in Hawaii, 188 were destroyed and 159 damaged, 155 of them on the ground.
[src:aaron-c-waters/attack-on-pearl-harbor-p01] Almost none were actually ready to take off to defend the base.
[src:aaron-c-waters/attack-on-pearl-harbor-p01] Eight Army Air Forces pilots managed to get airborne during the attack, and six were credited with downing at least one Japanese aircraft during the attack: 1st Lieutenant Lewis M.
[src:aaron-c-waters/attack-on-pearl-harbor-p01] Of 33 Consolidated PBY Catalinas in Hawaii, 30 were destroyed, while three on patrol at the time of the attack returned undamaged.
[src:aaron-c-waters/attack-on-pearl-harbor-p01] Friendly fire brought down some American planes on top of that, including four from an inbound flight from *Enterprise*.
[src:aaron-c-waters/attack-on-pearl-harbor-p01] At the time of the attack, nine civilian aircraft were flying in the vicinity of Pearl Harbor.
[src:aaron-c-waters/attack-on-pearl-harbor-p01] Fifty-five Japanese airmen and nine submariners were killed in the attack, and one, Kazuo Sakamaki, was captured.
[src:aaron-c-waters/attack-on-pearl-harbor-p01] Of Japan's 414 available planes, 350 took part in the raid.
[src:aaron-c-waters/attack-on-pearl-harbor-p01] Twenty-nine were lost, nine in the first wave (three fighters, one dive bomber, and five torpedo bombers) and twenty in the second (six fighters and fourteen dive bombers), with another 74 damaged by anti-aircraft fire from the ground.
[src:aaron-c-waters/attack-on-pearl-harbor-p01] According to some accounts, several Japanese junior officers, including Fuchida and Genda, urged Nagumo to carry out a third strike in order to sink more of Pearl Harbor's remaining warships, and damage the base's maintenance shops, drydock facilities and oil tank yards.
[src:aaron-c-waters/attack-on-pearl-harbor-p01] Most notably, Fuchida gave a firsthand account of this meeting several times after the war.
[src:aaron-c-waters/attack-on-pearl-harbor-p01] However, some historians have cast doubt on this and many other of Fuchida's later claims, which sometimes conflict with documented historic records.
[src:aaron-c-waters/attack-on-pearl-harbor-p01] Genda, who opined during the planning for the attack that without an invasion three strikes were necessary to fully destroy the Pacific Fleet, denied requesting an additional attack.
[src:aaron-c-waters/attack-on-pearl-harbor-p01] Although a hypothetical third strike would have likely focused on the base's remaining warships, military historians have suggested any potential damage to the shore facilities would have hampered the Pacific Fleet far more seriously.
[src:aaron-c-waters/attack-on-pearl-harbor-p01] If they had been wiped out, "serious [American] operations in the Pacific would have been postponed for more than a year"; according to Admiral Chester W.
[src:aaron-c-waters/attack-on-pearl-harbor-p01] Nimitz, later Commander in Chief of the Pacific Fleet, "it would have prolonged the war another two years".
[src:aaron-c-waters/attack-on-pearl-harbor-p01] At a conference aboard his flagship the following morning, Yamamoto supported Nagumo's withdrawal without launching a third wave.
[src:aaron-c-waters/attack-on-pearl-harbor-p01] In retrospect, sparing the vital dockyards, maintenance shops, and the oil tank farm meant the United States could respond relatively quickly in the Pacific.
[src:aaron-c-waters/attack-on-pearl-harbor-p01] Yamamoto later regretted Nagumo's decision to withdraw and categorically stated it had been a great mistake not to order a third strike.
[src:aaron-c-waters/attack-on-pearl-harbor-p01] Twenty-one American ships were damaged or lost in the attack, of which all but three were repaired and returned to service.
[src:aaron-c-waters/attack-on-pearl-harbor-p01] Five of these battleships would, after major repair, participate in the last-ever battleship-on-battleship engagement at the Battle of Surigao Strait, which would result in several Japanese losses, including two battleships.
[src:aaron-c-waters/attack-on-pearl-harbor-p01] After a systematic search for survivors, Captain Homer N.
[src:aaron-c-waters/attack-on-pearl-harbor-p01] Wallin was ordered to lead a formal salvage operation.
[src:aaron-c-waters/attack-on-pearl-harbor-p01] Around Pearl Harbor, divers from the Navy (shore and tenders), the Pearl Harbor Naval Shipyard, and civilian contractors (Pacific Bridge Company and others) began work on the ships that could be refloated.
[src:aaron-c-waters/attack-on-pearl-harbor-p01] They patched holes, cleared debris, and pumped water out of ships.
[src:aaron-c-waters/attack-on-pearl-harbor-p01] Melvin Storer and other Navy divers worked inside the damaged ships.
[src:aaron-c-waters/attack-on-pearl-harbor-p01] Within six months, five battleships and two cruisers were patched or refloated so they could be sent to shipyards in Pearl Harbor and on the mainland for extensive repair.
[src:aaron-c-waters/attack-on-pearl-harbor-p01] Intensive salvage operations continued for another year, a total of some 20,000 man-hours under water.
[src:aaron-c-waters/attack-on-pearl-harbor-p01] *Arizona* and the target ship *Utah* were too heavily damaged for salvage and remain where they were sunk, with *Arizona* becoming a war memorial.
[src:aaron-c-waters/attack-on-pearl-harbor-p01] *Oklahoma*, while raised, was never repaired and capsized while under tow to the mainland in 1947.
[src:aaron-c-waters/attack-on-pearl-harbor-p01] *Nevada* proved particularly difficult to raise and repair; two men involved in the operation died after inhaling poisonous gases that had accumulated in the ship's interior.
[src:aaron-c-waters/attack-on-pearl-harbor-p01] When feasible, armament and equipment were removed from vessels too damaged to repair and put to use to improve the anti-aircraft defense of the harbor or installed aboard other craft.
[src:aaron-c-waters/attack-on-pearl-harbor-p01] The initial announcement of the attack on Pearl Harbor was made by the White House Press Secretary, Stephen Early, at 2:22 p.m.
[src:aaron-c-waters/attack-on-pearl-harbor-p01] Initial reports of the attack moved on news wires at approximately 2:25 p.m.
[src:aaron-c-waters/attack-on-pearl-harbor-p01] The first radio coverage (which, at the time, represented the earliest opportunity for ordinary people to learn of the attack) was on the CBS radio network's scheduled news program, *World News Today*, at 2:30 p.m.
[src:aaron-c-waters/attack-on-pearl-harbor-p01] John Charles Daly read the initial report, then switched to London, where Robert Trout ad-libbed on the possible London reaction.
[src:aaron-c-waters/attack-on-pearl-harbor-p01] The first report on NBC cut into a play, a dramatization of *The Inspector-General*, at 2:33 p.m.
[src:aaron-c-waters/attack-on-pearl-harbor-p01] Eastern time and lasted only 21 seconds.
[src:aaron-c-waters/attack-on-pearl-harbor-p01] Unlike the later practice with major news stories, there were only brief interruptions of scheduled commercial programming.
[src:aaron-c-waters/attack-on-pearl-harbor-p01] WNBT from New York was the only TV station that was regularly airing that day in the country, with the comedy movie *Millionaire Playboy*, which was scheduled for 3:30-4:30 PM, being interrupted with the news of the attack.
[src:aaron-c-waters/attack-on-pearl-harbor-p01] The other station known to cover the attacks was WCBW, also out of New York, where a special report on the attack was broadcast that evening.
[src:aaron-c-waters/attack-on-pearl-harbor-p01] There are no recordings of either station's coverage, either visual or audio.
[src:aaron-c-waters/attack-on-pearl-harbor-p01] At the time of the attack, the last three regular season National Football League games were happening.
[src:aaron-c-waters/attack-on-pearl-harbor-p01] The Chicago Bears were playing the Chicago Cardinals at Comiskey Park; the Brooklyn Dodgers were playing the New York Giants at the Polo Grounds; and the Philadelphia Eagles were playing the Washington Redskins at Washington's Griffith Stadium.
[src:aaron-c-waters/attack-on-pearl-harbor-p01] All three games were in progress as the attacks began, and no official announcements were made at any of the games concerning the attacks, with many fans finding out from phone calls placed at the stadium or from newsboys outside the stadium.
[src:aaron-c-waters/attack-on-pearl-harbor-p01] However, throughout the Redskins game, happening in Washington, many military, government and diplomatic personnel were asked to call their offices or return to them.
[src:aaron-c-waters/attack-on-pearl-harbor-p01] Donovan, was paged to call his office immediately, and all military personnel were asked to return to their stations at the conclusion of the game.
[src:aaron-c-waters/attack-on-pearl-harbor-p01] The Washington game, thanks to the announcements and general curiosity of the happenings, ended in a near-empty stadium.
[src:aaron-c-waters/attack-on-pearl-harbor-p01] A contemporaneous newspaper report compared the attack to the Battle of Port Arthur in which the Imperial Japanese Navy attacked the Imperial Russian Navy, triggering the Russo-Japanese War, 37 years prior.
[src:aaron-c-waters/attack-on-pearl-harbor-p01] Modern writers have continued to note parallels between the attacks, albeit more dispassionately.
[src:aaron-c-waters/attack-on-pearl-harbor-p01] News of the attack was first broadcast at 11:30 AM (Japanese Standard Time), however it had already been announced "shortly after" 7 AM (Japanese Standard Time) that Japan had "entered into a situation of war with the United States and Britain in the Western Pacific before dawn".
[src:aaron-c-waters/attack-on-pearl-harbor-p01] There was no further elaboration or explanation, and the attacks were already finished by that time.
[src:aaron-c-waters/attack-on-pearl-harbor-p01] The attack on Pearl Harbor was eventually covered in the Japanese press, but press in wartime Japan was heavily censored.
[src:aaron-c-waters/attack-on-pearl-harbor-p01] One Japanese newspaper, *The* *Asahi Shimbun* did report on the attack the day it occurred, and from that point onward their editorials began to back governmental decisions regardless of what they were.
[src:aaron-c-waters/attack-on-pearl-harbor-p01] The *Asahi Shimbun* also reported the declaration of war on the United States after the attacks, framing it as an Imperial Order, with most Japanese people taking it that way.
[src:aaron-c-waters/attack-on-pearl-harbor-p01] In contrast, coverage in *The New York Times* focused on "the danger to democracy and to the nation" brought on by the Japanese attack.
[src:aaron-c-waters/attack-on-pearl-harbor-p01] NHK broadcast twelve special news reports along with its six regularly scheduled ones that day.
[src:aaron-c-waters/attack-on-pearl-harbor-p01] NHK covered the news of Pearl Harbor and other attacks positively throughout the rest of the month.
[src:aaron-c-waters/attack-on-pearl-harbor-p01] The United Kingdom's BBC broadcast news of the attack and that Manila was also under attack.
[src:aaron-c-waters/attack-on-pearl-harbor-p02] The day after the attack, US President Franklin D.
[src:aaron-c-waters/attack-on-pearl-harbor-p02] Roosevelt delivered his famous Day of Infamy speech to a Joint Session of Congress, calling for a formal declaration of war on the Empire of Japan.
[src:aaron-c-waters/attack-on-pearl-harbor-p02] Congress obliged his request less than an hour later.
[src:aaron-c-waters/attack-on-pearl-harbor-p02] On December 11, Germany and Italy declared war on the United States, even though the Tripartite Pact did not require it.
[src:aaron-c-waters/attack-on-pearl-harbor-p02] Congress issued a declaration of war against Germany and Italy later that same day.
[src:aaron-c-waters/attack-on-pearl-harbor-p02] The United Kingdom had already been at war with Germany since September 1939 and with Italy since June 1940, and British Prime Minister Winston Churchill had promised to declare war "within the hour" of a Japanese attack on the United States.
[src:aaron-c-waters/attack-on-pearl-harbor-p02] Upon learning of the Japanese attacks on Malaya, Singapore, and Hong Kong, Churchill promptly determined there was no need to either wait or further consult the US government and immediately summoned the Japanese ambassador.
[src:aaron-c-waters/attack-on-pearl-harbor-p02] As a result, the United Kingdom declared war on Japan nine hours before the United States did.
[src:aaron-c-waters/attack-on-pearl-harbor-p02] The attack was a shock to all the Allies in the Pacific Theater.
[src:aaron-c-waters/attack-on-pearl-harbor-p02] Further losses compounded the alarming setback.
[src:aaron-c-waters/attack-on-pearl-harbor-p02] Japan began the Philippines campaign (1941–1942) hours later (because of the time difference, it was December 8 in the Philippines).
[src:aaron-c-waters/attack-on-pearl-harbor-p02] Only three days after the attack on Pearl Harbor, *Prince of Wales* and *Repulse* were sunk off Malaya.
[src:aaron-c-waters/attack-on-pearl-harbor-p02] Churchill recollected "In all the war I never received a more direct shock.
[src:aaron-c-waters/attack-on-pearl-harbor-p02] As I turned and twisted in bed the full horror of the news sank in upon me.
[src:aaron-c-waters/attack-on-pearl-harbor-p02] There were no British or American capital ships in the Indian Ocean or the Pacific except the American survivors of Pearl Harbor who were hastening back to California.
[src:aaron-c-waters/attack-on-pearl-harbor-p02] Throughout the war, Pearl Harbor was frequently used in American propaganda.
[src:aaron-c-waters/attack-on-pearl-harbor-p02] The bombing of Pearl Harbor would not persuade controversial Detroit area priest Charles Coughlin to support US entry into World War II, with Coughlin even alleging that Jews had planned the war for their own benefit and had conspired to involve the United States.
[src:aaron-c-waters/attack-on-pearl-harbor-p02] One further consequence of the attack on Pearl Harbor and its aftermath (notably the Niʻihau incident) was that Japanese-American residents and citizens were imprisoned in nearby Japanese-American internment camps.
[src:aaron-c-waters/attack-on-pearl-harbor-p02] Within hours of the attack, hundreds of Japanese-American leaders were rounded up and taken to high-security camps such as Sand Island at the mouth of Honolulu harbor and Kilauea Military Camp on the island of Hawaii.
[src:aaron-c-waters/attack-on-pearl-harbor-p02] Eventually, more than 110,000 Japanese Americans, nearly all who lived on the West Coast, were forced into interior camps, but in Hawaii, where the 150,000-plus Japanese Americans composed over one-third of the population, only 1,200 to 1,800 were interned.
[src:aaron-c-waters/attack-on-pearl-harbor-p02] The attack also had international consequences.
[src:aaron-c-waters/attack-on-pearl-harbor-p02] The Canadian province of British Columbia, bordering the Pacific Ocean, had long had a large population of Japanese immigrants and their Japanese-Canadian descendants.
[src:aaron-c-waters/attack-on-pearl-harbor-p02] Pre-war tensions were exacerbated by the Pearl Harbor attack, leading to a reaction from the government of Canada.
[src:aaron-c-waters/attack-on-pearl-harbor-p02] On February 24, 1942, Order-in-Council P.C. no.
[src:aaron-c-waters/attack-on-pearl-harbor-p02] 1486 was issued under the War Measures Act, allowing for the forced removal of any and all Canadians of Japanese descent from British Columbia and prohibiting them from returning to the province.
[src:aaron-c-waters/attack-on-pearl-harbor-p02] On March 4, regulations under the act were adopted to expel Japanese Canadians.
[src:aaron-c-waters/attack-on-pearl-harbor-p02] As a result, 12,000 were interned in interior camps, 2,000 were sent to road camps, and another 2,000 were forced to work in the prairies on sugar beet farms.
[src:aaron-c-waters/attack-on-pearl-harbor-p02] Additionally, a special military award, the Pearl Harbor Commemorative Medal, was later authorized for all military veterans of the attack.
[src:aaron-c-waters/attack-on-pearl-harbor-p02] Japanese planners of the Pearl Harbor attack had determined that some means were required for rescuing fliers whose aircraft were damaged too badly to return to the carriers.
[src:aaron-c-waters/attack-on-pearl-harbor-p02] The island of Niʻihau, only thirty minutes by air from Pearl Harbor, was designated as the rescue point.
[src:aaron-c-waters/attack-on-pearl-harbor-p02] During the second wave, a Zero fighter flown by Petty Officer Shigenori Nishikaichi of *Hiryu* was damaged in the attack on Wheeler, so he flew to the rescue point.
[src:aaron-c-waters/attack-on-pearl-harbor-p02] The aircraft was further damaged on his crash landing.
[src:aaron-c-waters/attack-on-pearl-harbor-p02] Nishikaichi was helped from the wreckage by one of the Native Hawaiians, who, aware of the tension between the United States and Japan, took the pilot's pistol, maps, codes and other documents.
[src:aaron-c-waters/attack-on-pearl-harbor-p02] The island's residents had no telephones or radios and were completely unaware of the attack on Pearl Harbor.
[src:aaron-c-waters/attack-on-pearl-harbor-p02] Nishikaichi enlisted the support of three Japanese-American residents in an attempt to recover the documents.
[src:aaron-c-waters/attack-on-pearl-harbor-p02] During the ensuing struggles, Nishikaichi was killed, and a Hawaiian civilian was wounded; one collaborator committed suicide, and his wife and the third collaborator were sent to prison.
[src:aaron-c-waters/attack-on-pearl-harbor-p02] The ease with which the local ethnic Japanese residents had apparently gone to Nishikaichi's assistance was a source of concern for many and tended to support those who believed that local Japanese could not be trusted.
[src:aaron-c-waters/attack-on-pearl-harbor-p02] While the attack accomplished its intended objective, it turned out to be largely unnecessary.
[src:aaron-c-waters/attack-on-pearl-harbor-p02] Unknown to Yamamoto, who conceived the original plan, the United States Navy had decided as far back as 1935 to abandon "charging" across the Pacific towards the Philippines in response to an outbreak of war (in keeping with the evolution of Plan Orange).
[src:aaron-c-waters/attack-on-pearl-harbor-p02] The United States instead adopted "Plan Dog" in 1940, which emphasized keeping the IJN out of the eastern Pacific and away from the shipping lanes to Australia, while the United States concentrated on defeating Nazi Germany.
[src:aaron-c-waters/attack-on-pearl-harbor-p02] Fortunately for the United States, the American aircraft carriers were untouched; otherwise, the Pacific Fleet's ability to conduct offensive operations would have been crippled for a year or more (given no diversions from the Atlantic Fleet).
[src:aaron-c-waters/attack-on-pearl-harbor-p02] As it was, the Navy was left with no choice but to rely on carriers and submarines.
[src:aaron-c-waters/attack-on-pearl-harbor-p02] While six of the eight battleships were repaired and returned to service, their relatively low speed and high fuel consumption limited their deployment, and they served mainly in shore bombardment roles (their only major action being the Battle of Surigao Strait in October 1944).
[src:aaron-c-waters/attack-on-pearl-harbor-p02] A major flaw in Japanese strategic thinking was their reliance on *Kantai Kessen*, a belief that the ultimate Pacific battle would be fought by battleships, in keeping with the doctrine of Captain Alfred Thayer Mahan.
[src:aaron-c-waters/attack-on-pearl-harbor-p02] As a result, Yamamoto (and his successors) hoarded battleships for a "decisive battle" that never happened.
[src:aaron-c-waters/attack-on-pearl-harbor-p02] The Japanese confidence in their ability to win a quick victory meant that they neglected Pearl Harbor's navy repair yards, oil tank farms, submarine base, and old headquarters building.
[src:aaron-c-waters/attack-on-pearl-harbor-p02] All of these targets were omitted from Genda's list, yet they proved more important than any battleship to the American war effort in the Pacific.
[src:aaron-c-waters/attack-on-pearl-harbor-p02] The survival of the repair shops and fuel depots allowed Pearl Harbor to maintain logistical support of the Navy, such as the Doolittle Raid, the Battle of the Coral Sea, and the Battle of Midway.
[src:aaron-c-waters/attack-on-pearl-harbor-p02] Lastly, the basement of the Old Administration Building was the home of the cryptanalytic unit that contributed significantly to the Midway ambush and the submarine force's success.
[src:aaron-c-waters/attack-on-pearl-harbor-p02] The Japanese failure to follow up their attack on Pearl Harbor with an invasion of Hawaii was also seen as another strategic failure, although experts find it unlikely Japan could have pulled off such a feat.
[src:aaron-c-waters/attack-on-pearl-harbor-p02] Japan had long seen Hawaii as a part of their planned Pacific empire.
[src:aaron-c-waters/attack-on-pearl-harbor-p02] As early as 1932 and even 1924, Admiral Seijiro Kawashima and Commander Hironori Mizuno argued that in the event of any war with the United States, Japan needed to take Hawaii, and a failure to do so would doom the war to being prolonged, and keep Japan from being able to win.
[src:aaron-c-waters/attack-on-pearl-harbor-p02] Before the Pearl Harbor attack, Japanese intelligence officer Kinoaki Matsuo and Japanese Commander Minuro Genda were both in favor of invading Hawaii, believing that such a move was necessary for forcing the US to the negotiating table and winning the war.
[src:aaron-c-waters/attack-on-pearl-harbor-p02] However, in the wake of discussions following the war games drilling for the Pearl Harbor attack on 5–17 September 1941, Admiral Isoroku Yamamoto ultimately decided against attempting an invasion of Hawaii.
[src:aaron-c-waters/attack-on-pearl-harbor-p02] On 9 December, two days after the attack, Admiral Yamamoto apparently changed his mind, and realizing the strategic blunder in failing to seize Oahu, decided to prepare plans for an invasion of Hawaii, which was dubbed the "Yamaguchi Plan".
[src:aaron-c-waters/attack-on-pearl-harbor-p02] The plan consisted of seizing Midway Island, Johnston Atoll, and Palmyra Island, and imposing a tightening blockade on Oahu.
[src:aaron-c-waters/attack-on-pearl-harbor-p02] After seizing the Big Island of Hawaii, Oahu would fall to an amphibious assault.
[src:aaron-c-waters/attack-on-pearl-harbor-p02] However, Japan's decisive defeat at the Battle of Midway in June 1942 permanently scuttled those plans.
[src:aaron-c-waters/attack-on-pearl-harbor-p02] There has been debate as to how and why the United States had been caught unaware, and how much and when American officials knew of Japanese plans and related topics.
[src:aaron-c-waters/attack-on-pearl-harbor-p02] As early as 1924, Chief of United States Air Service Mason Patrick showed concern for military vulnerabilities in the Pacific, having sent General Billy Mitchell on a survey of the Pacific and the East.
[src:aaron-c-waters/attack-on-pearl-harbor-p02] Patrick called Mitchell's subsequent report, which identified vulnerabilities in Hawaii, a "theoretical treatise on employment of airpower in the Pacific, which, in all probability undoubtedly will be of extreme value some 10 or 15 years hence".
[src:aaron-c-waters/attack-on-pearl-harbor-p02] At least two naval war games, one in 1932 and another in 1936, proved that Pearl was vulnerable to such an attack.
[src:aaron-c-waters/attack-on-pearl-harbor-p02] Admiral James Richardson was removed from command shortly after protesting President Roosevelt's decision to move the bulk of the Pacific fleet to Pearl Harbor.
[src:aaron-c-waters/attack-on-pearl-harbor-p02] The decisions of military and political leadership to ignore these warnings have contributed to conspiracy theories.
[src:aaron-c-waters/attack-on-pearl-harbor-p02] However, this conspiracy theory is rejected by mainstream historians.
[src:aaron-c-waters/attack-on-pearl-harbor-p02] The theory that the Americans were warned in advance, however, is supported by statements made by Dick Ellis, a British-Australian intelligence officer for MI6 who helped William J.
[src:aaron-c-waters/attack-on-pearl-harbor-p02] Donovan set up the Office of Strategic Services.
[src:aaron-c-waters/attack-on-pearl-harbor-p02] Ellis was deputy to William Stephenson at British Security Co-ordination.
[src:aaron-c-waters/attack-on-pearl-harbor-p02] In Jesse Fink's 2023 biography of Ellis, *The Eagle in the Mirror*, Ellis is quoted as saying: "[Stephenson] was convinced from the information that was reaching him that this attack was imminent, and through Jimmy Roosevelt, President Roosevelt's son, he passed this information to the President.
[src:aaron-c-waters/attack-on-pearl-harbor-p02] The US Navy's "Washington chief" during the Pearl Harbor attack was Admiral Harold R.
[src:aaron-c-waters/attack-on-pearl-harbor-p02] Stark, who was the Chief of Naval Operations.
[src:aaron-c-waters/basalt] Molten basalt lava has a low viscosity due to its relatively low silica content (between 45% and 52%), resulting in rapidly moving lava flows that can spread over great areas before cooling and solidifying.
[src:aaron-c-waters/basalt] Flood basalts are thick sequences of many such flows that can cover hundreds of thousands of square kilometres and constitute the most voluminous of all volcanic formations.
[src:aaron-c-waters/basalt] Basaltic magmas within Earth are thought to originate from the upper mantle.
[src:aaron-c-waters/basalt] The chemistry of basalts thus provides clues to processes deep in Earth's interior.
[src:aaron-c-waters/basalt] Basalt is composed mostly of oxides of silicon, iron, magnesium, potassium, aluminium, titanium, and calcium.
[src:aaron-c-waters/basalt] Geologists classify igneous rock by its mineral content whenever possible; the relative volume percentages of quartz (crystalline silica (SiO2)), alkali feldspar, plagioclase, and feldspathoid (QAPF) are particularly important.
[src:aaron-c-waters/basalt] An aphanitic (fine-grained) igneous rock is classified as basalt when its QAPF fraction is composed of less than 10% feldspathoid and less than 20% quartz, and plagioclase makes up at least 65% of its feldspar content.
[src:aaron-c-waters/basalt] This places basalt in the basalt/andesite field of the QAPF diagram.
[src:aaron-c-waters/basalt] Basalt is further distinguished from andesite by its silica content of under 52%.
[src:aaron-c-waters/basalt] This places basalt in the B field of the TAS diagram.
[src:aaron-c-waters/basalt] Such a composition is described as mafic.
[src:aaron-c-waters/basalt] Basalt is usually dark grey to black in colour, due to a high content of augite or other dark-coloured pyroxene minerals, but can exhibit a wide range of shading.
[src:aaron-c-waters/basalt] Some basalts are quite light-coloured due to a high content of plagioclase; these are sometimes described as *leucobasalts*.
[src:aaron-c-waters/basalt] It can be difficult to distinguish between lighter-colored basalt and andesite, so field researchers commonly use a rule of thumb for this purpose, classifying it as basalt if it has a color index of 35 or greater.
[src:aaron-c-waters/basalt] The physical properties of basalt result from its relatively low silica content and typically high iron and magnesium content.
[src:aaron-c-waters/basalt] The average density of basalt is 2.9 g/cm3, compared, for example, to granite’s typical density of 2.7 g/cm3.
[src:aaron-c-waters/basalt] The viscosity of basaltic magma is relatively low—around 104 to 105 cP—similar to the viscosity of ketchup, but that is still several orders of magnitude higher than the viscosity of water, which is about 1 cP).
[src:aaron-c-waters/basalt] Basalt is often porphyritic, containing larger crystals (phenocrysts) that formed before the extrusion event that brought the magma to the surface, embedded in a finer-grained matrix.
[src:aaron-c-waters/basalt] These phenocrysts are usually made of augite, olivine, or a calcium-rich plagioclase, which have the highest melting temperatures of any of the minerals that can typically crystallize from the melt, and which are therefore the first to form solid crystals.
[src:aaron-c-waters/basalt] Basalt often contains vesicles; they are formed when dissolved gases bubble out of the magma as it decompresses during its approach to the surface; the erupted lava then solidifies before the gases can escape.
[src:aaron-c-waters/basalt] When vesicles make up a substantial fraction of the volume of the rock, the rock is described as scoria.
[src:aaron-c-waters/basalt] Diabase and gabbro are thus the hypabyssal and plutonic equivalents of basalt.
[src:aaron-c-waters/basalt] During the Hadean, Archean, and early Proterozoic eons of Earth's history, the chemistry of erupted magmas was significantly different from what it is today, due to immature crustal and asthenosphere differentiation.
[src:aaron-c-waters/basalt] The resulting ultramafic volcanic rocks, with silica (SiO2) contents below 45% and high magnesium oxide (MgO) content, are usually classified as komatiites.
[src:aaron-c-waters/basalt] The word "basalt" is ultimately derived from Late Latin *basaltes*, a misspelling of Latin *basanites* "very hard stone", which was imported from Ancient Greek βασανίτης (*basanites*), from βάσανος (**basanos**, "touchstone").
[src:aaron-c-waters/basalt] The modern petrological term *basalt*, describing a particular composition of lava-derived rock, became standard because of its use by Georgius Agricola in 1546, in his work *De Natura Fossilium*.
[src:aaron-c-waters/basalt] Agricola applied the term "basalt" to the volcanic black rock beneath the Bishop of Meissen's Stolpen castle, believing it to be the same as the "basaniten" described by Pliny the Elder in AD 77 in *Naturalis Historiae*.
[src:aaron-c-waters/basalt] On Earth, most basalt is formed by decompression melting of the mantle.
[src:aaron-c-waters/basalt] The high pressure in the upper mantle (due to the weight of the overlying rock) raises the melting point of mantle rock, so that almost all of the upper mantle is solid.
[src:aaron-c-waters/basalt] However, mantle rock is ductile (the solid rock slowly deforms under high stress).
[src:aaron-c-waters/basalt] When tectonic forces cause hot mantle rock to creep upwards, pressure on the ascending rock decreases, and this can lower its melting point enough for the rock to partially melt, producing basaltic magma.
[src:aaron-c-waters/basalt] Decompression melting can occur in a variety of tectonic settings, including in continental rift zones, at mid-ocean ridges, above geological hotspots, and in back-arc basins.
[src:aaron-c-waters/basalt] Basalt also forms in subduction zones, where mantle rock rises into a mantle wedge above the descending slab.
[src:aaron-c-waters/basalt] The slab releases water vapor and other volatiles as it descends, which further lowers the melting point, further increasing the amount of decompression melting.
[src:aaron-c-waters/basalt] Each tectonic setting produces basalt with its own distinctive characteristics.
[src:aaron-c-waters/basalt] The mineralogy of basalt is characterized by a preponderance of calcic plagioclase feldspar and pyroxene.
[src:aaron-c-waters/basalt] Olivine can also be a significant constituent.
[src:aaron-c-waters/basalt] Accessory minerals present in relatively minor amounts include iron oxides and iron-titanium oxides, such as magnetite, ulvöspinel, and ilmenite.
[src:aaron-c-waters/basalt] Because of the presence of such oxide minerals, basalt can acquire strong magnetic signatures as it cools, and paleomagnetic studies have made extensive use of basalt.
[src:aaron-c-waters/basalt] In tholeiitic basalt, pyroxene (augite and orthopyroxene or pigeonite) and calcium-rich plagioclase are common phenocryst minerals.
[src:aaron-c-waters/basalt] Olivine may also be a phenocryst, and when present, may have rims of pigeonite.
[src:aaron-c-waters/basalt] The groundmass contains interstitial quartz or tridymite or cristobalite.
[src:aaron-c-waters/basalt] *Olivine tholeiitic basalt* has augite and orthopyroxene or pigeonite with abundant olivine, but olivine may have rims of pyroxene and is unlikely to be present in the groundmass.
[src:aaron-c-waters/basalt] Alkali basalts typically have mineral assemblages that lack orthopyroxene but contain olivine.
[src:aaron-c-waters/basalt] Feldspar phenocrysts typically are labradorite to andesine in composition.
[src:aaron-c-waters/basalt] Augite is rich in titanium compared to augite in tholeiitic basalt.
[src:aaron-c-waters/basalt] Minerals such as alkali feldspar, leucite, nepheline, sodalite, phlogopite mica, and apatite may be present in the groundmass.
[src:aaron-c-waters/basalt] Basalt has high liquidus and solidus temperatures—values at the Earth's surface are near or above 1200 °C (liquidus) and near or below 1000 °C (solidus); these values are higher than those of other common igneous rocks.
[src:aaron-c-waters/basalt] The majority of tholeiitic basalts are formed at approximately 50–100 km depth within the mantle.
[src:aaron-c-waters/basalt] Many alkali basalts may be formed at greater depths, perhaps as deep as 150–200 km.
[src:aaron-c-waters/basalt] The origin of high-alumina basalt continues to be controversial, with disagreement over whether it is a primary melt or derived from other basalt types by fractionation.
[src:aaron-c-waters/basalt] Relative to most common igneous rocks, basalt compositions are rich in MgO and CaO and low in SiO2 and the alkali oxides, i.e., Na2O + K2O, consistent with their TAS classification.
[src:aaron-c-waters/basalt] Basalt contains more silica than picrobasalt and most basanites and tephrites but less than basaltic andesite.
[src:aaron-c-waters/basalt] Basalt has a lower total content of alkali oxides than trachybasalt and most basanites and tephrites.
[src:aaron-c-waters/basalt] Basalt generally has a composition of 45–52 wt% SiO2, 2–5 wt% total alkalis, 0.5–2.0 wt% TiO2, 5–14 wt% FeO and 14 wt% or more Al2O3.
[src:aaron-c-waters/basalt] Contents of CaO are commonly near 10 wt%, those of MgO commonly in the range 5 to 12 wt%.
[src:aaron-c-waters/basalt] High-alumina basalts have aluminium contents of 17–19 wt% Al2O3; boninites have magnesium (MgO) contents of up to 15 percent.
[src:aaron-c-waters/basalt] Rare feldspathoid-rich mafic rocks, akin to alkali basalts, may have Na2O + K2O contents of 12% or more.
[src:aaron-c-waters/basalt] The abundances of the lanthanide or rare-earth elements (REE) can be a useful diagnostic tool to help explain the history of mineral crystallisation as the melt cooled.
[src:aaron-c-waters/basalt] In particular, the relative abundance of europium compared to the other REE is often markedly higher or lower, and called the europium anomaly.
[src:aaron-c-waters/basalt] It arises because Eu2+ can substitute for Ca2+ in plagioclase feldspar, unlike any of the other lanthanides, which tend to only form 3+ cations.
[src:aaron-c-waters/basalt] Mid-ocean ridge basalts (MORB) and their intrusive equivalents, gabbros, are the characteristic igneous rocks formed at mid-ocean ridges.
[src:aaron-c-waters/basalt] They are tholeiitic basalts particularly low in total alkalis and in incompatible trace elements, and they have relatively flat REE patterns normalized to mantle or chondrite values.
[src:aaron-c-waters/basalt] In contrast, alkali basalts have normalized patterns highly enriched in the light REE, and with greater abundances of the REE and of other incompatible elements.
[src:aaron-c-waters/basalt] Because MORB basalt is considered a key to understanding plate tectonics, its compositions have been much studied.
[src:aaron-c-waters/basalt] Although MORB compositions are distinctive relative to average compositions of basalts erupted in other environments, they are not uniform.
[src:aaron-c-waters/basalt] For instance, compositions change with position along the Mid-Atlantic Ridge, and the compositions also define different ranges in different ocean basins.
[src:aaron-c-waters/basalt] Mid-ocean ridge basalts have been subdivided into varieties such as normal (NMORB) and those slightly more enriched in incompatible elements (EMORB).
[src:aaron-c-waters/basalt] Isotope ratios of elements such as strontium, neodymium, lead, hafnium, and osmium in basalts have been much studied to learn about the evolution of the Earth's mantle.
[src:aaron-c-waters/basalt] Isotopic ratios of noble gases, such as 3He/4He, are also of great value: for instance, ratios for basalts range from 6 to 10 for mid-ocean ridge tholeiitic basalt (normalized to atmospheric values), but to 15–24 and more for ocean-island basalts thought to be derived from mantle plumes.
[src:aaron-c-waters/basalt] Source rocks for the partial melts that produce basaltic magma probably include both peridotite and pyroxenite.
[src:aaron-c-waters/basalt] The shape, structure and texture of a basalt is diagnostic of how and where it erupted—for example, whether into the sea, in an explosive cinder eruption or as creeping pāhoehoe lava flows, the classic image of Hawaiian basalt eruptions.
[src:aaron-c-waters/basalt] Basalt that erupts under open air (that is, subaerially) forms three distinct types of lava or volcanic deposits: scoria; ash or cinder (breccia); and lava flows.
[src:aaron-c-waters/basalt] Basalt in the tops of subaerial lava flows and cinder cones will often be highly vesiculated, imparting a lightweight "frothy" texture to the rock.
[src:aaron-c-waters/basalt] Basaltic cinders are often red, coloured by oxidized iron from weathered iron-rich minerals such as pyroxene.
[src:aaron-c-waters/basalt] ʻAʻā types of blocky cinder and breccia flows of thick, viscous basaltic lava are common in Hawaiʻi.
[src:aaron-c-waters/basalt] Pāhoehoe is a highly fluid, hot form of basalt which tends to form thin aprons of molten lava which fill up hollows and sometimes forms lava lakes.
[src:aaron-c-waters/basalt] Lava tubes are common features of pāhoehoe eruptions.
[src:aaron-c-waters/basalt] Basaltic tuff or pyroclastic rocks are less common than basaltic lava flows.
[src:aaron-c-waters/basalt] Usually basalt is too hot and fluid to build up sufficient pressure to form explosive lava eruptions but occasionally this will happen by trapping of the lava within the volcanic throat and buildup of volcanic gases.
[src:aaron-c-waters/basalt] Hawaiʻi's Mauna Loa volcano erupted in this way in the 19th century, as did Mount Tarawera, New Zealand in its violent 1886 eruption.
[src:aaron-c-waters/basalt] Maar volcanoes are typical of small basalt tuffs, formed by explosive eruption of basalt through the crust, forming an apron of mixed basalt and wall rock breccia and a fan of basalt tuff further out from the volcano.
[src:aaron-c-waters/basalt] Amygdaloidal structure is common in relict vesicles and beautifully crystallized species of zeolites, quartz or calcite are frequently found.
[src:aaron-c-waters/basalt] During the cooling of a thick lava flow, contractional joints or fractures form.
[src:aaron-c-waters/basalt] If a flow cools relatively rapidly, significant contraction forces build up.
[src:aaron-c-waters/basalt] While a flow can shrink in the vertical dimension without fracturing, it cannot easily accommodate shrinking in the horizontal direction unless cracks form; the extensive fracture network that develops results in the formation of columns.
[src:aaron-c-waters/basalt] These structures, or basalt prisms, are predominantly hexagonal in cross-section, but polygons with three to twelve or more sides can be observed.
[src:aaron-c-waters/basalt] The size of the columns depends loosely on the rate of cooling; very rapid cooling may result in very small (<1 cm diameter) columns, while slow cooling is more likely to produce large columns.
[src:aaron-c-waters/basalt] The character of submarine basalt eruptions is largely determined by depth of water, since increased pressure restricts the release of volatile gases and results in effusive eruptions.
[src:aaron-c-waters/basalt] It has been estimated that at depths greater than 500 metres (1,600 ft), explosive activity associated with basaltic magma is suppressed.
[src:aaron-c-waters/basalt] Above this depth, submarine eruptions are often explosive, tending to produce pyroclastic rock rather than basalt flows.
[src:aaron-c-waters/basalt] These eruptions, described as Surtseyan, are characterised by large quantities of steam and gas and the creation of large amounts of pumice.
[src:aaron-c-waters/basalt] When basalt erupts underwater or flows into the sea, contact with the water quenches the surface and the lava forms a distinctive *pillow* shape, through which the hot lava breaks to form another pillow.
[src:aaron-c-waters/basalt] This "pillow" texture is very common in underwater basaltic flows and is diagnostic of an underwater eruption environment when found in ancient rocks.
[src:aaron-c-waters/basalt] Pillows typically consist of a fine-grained core with a glassy crust and have radial jointing.
[src:aaron-c-waters/basalt] The size of individual pillows varies from 10 cm up to several metres.
[src:aaron-c-waters/basalt] When *pāhoehoe* lava enters the sea it usually forms pillow basalts.
[src:aaron-c-waters/basalt] However, when *ʻaʻā* enters the ocean it forms a littoral cone, a small cone-shaped accumulation of tuffaceous debris formed when the blocky *ʻaʻā* lava enters the water and explodes from built-up steam.
[src:aaron-c-waters/basalt] The island of Surtsey in the Atlantic Ocean is a basalt volcano which breached the ocean surface in 1963.
[src:aaron-c-waters/basalt] The initial phase of Surtsey's eruption was highly explosive, as the magma was quite fluid, causing the rock to be blown apart by the boiling steam to form a tuff and cinder cone.
[src:aaron-c-waters/basalt] This has subsequently moved to a typical pāhoehoe-type behaviour.
[src:aaron-c-waters/basalt] Volcanic glass may be present, particularly as rinds on rapidly chilled surfaces of lava flows, and is commonly (but not exclusively) associated with underwater eruptions.
[src:aaron-c-waters/basalt] Pillow basalt is also produced by some subglacial volcanic eruptions.
[src:aaron-c-waters/basalt] Basalt is the most common volcanic rock type on Earth, making up over 90% of all volcanic rock on the planet.
[src:aaron-c-waters/basalt] The crustal portions of oceanic tectonic plates are composed predominantly of basalt, produced from upwelling mantle below the ocean ridges.
[src:aaron-c-waters/basalt] Basalt is also the principal volcanic rock in many oceanic islands, including the islands of Hawaiʻi, the Faroe Islands, and Réunion.
[src:aaron-c-waters/basalt] The eruption of basalt lava is observed by geologists at about 20 volcanoes per year.
[src:aaron-c-waters/basalt] Basalt is the rock most typical of large igneous provinces.
[src:aaron-c-waters/basalt] These include continental flood basalts, the most voluminous basalts found on land.
[src:aaron-c-waters/basalt] Examples of continental flood basalts included the Deccan Traps in India, the Chilcotin Group in British Columbia, Canada, the Paraná Traps in Brazil, the Siberian Traps in Russia, the Karoo flood basalt province in South Africa, and the Columbia River Plateau of Washington and Oregon.
[src:aaron-c-waters/basalt] Basalt is also prevalent across extensive regions of the Eastern Galilee, Golan, and Bashan in Israel and Syria.
[src:aaron-c-waters/basalt] Basalt also is common around volcanic arcs, specially those on thin crust.
[src:aaron-c-waters/basalt] Ancient Precambrian basalts are usually only found in fold and thrust belts, and are often heavily metamorphosed.
[src:aaron-c-waters/basalt] These are known as greenstone belts, because low-grade metamorphism of basalt produces chlorite, actinolite, epidote and other green minerals.
[src:aaron-c-waters/basalt] As well as forming large parts of the Earth's crust, basalt also occurs in other parts of the Solar System.
[src:aaron-c-waters/basalt] Basalt commonly erupts on Io (the third largest moon of Jupiter), and has also formed on the Moon, Mars, Venus, and the asteroid Vesta.
[src:aaron-c-waters/basalt] The dark areas visible on Earth's moon, the lunar maria, are plains of flood basaltic lava flows.
[src:aaron-c-waters/basalt] These rocks were sampled both by the crewed American Apollo program and the robotic Russian Luna program, and are represented among the lunar meteorites.
[src:aaron-c-waters/basalt] Lunar basalts differ from their Earth counterparts principally in their high iron contents, which typically range from about 17 to 22 wt% FeO.
[src:aaron-c-waters/basalt] They also possess a wide range of titanium concentrations (present in the mineral ilmenite), ranging from less than 1 wt% TiO2, to about 13 wt.%.
[src:aaron-c-waters/basalt] Traditionally, lunar basalts have been classified according to their titanium content, with classes being named high-Ti, low-Ti, and very-low-Ti.
[src:aaron-c-waters/basalt] Nevertheless, global geochemical maps of titanium obtained from the Clementine mission demonstrate that the lunar maria possess a continuum of titanium concentrations, and that the highest concentrations are the least abundant.
[src:aaron-c-waters/basalt] Lunar basalts show exotic textures and mineralogy, particularly shock metamorphism, lack of the oxidation typical of terrestrial basalts, and a complete lack of hydration.
[src:aaron-c-waters/basalt] Most of the Moon's basalts erupted between about 3 and 3.5 billion years ago, but the oldest samples are 4.2 billion years old, and the youngest flows, based on the age dating method of crater counting, are estimated to have erupted only 1.2 billion years ago.
[src:aaron-c-waters/basalt] From 1972 to 1985, five Venera and two VEGA landers successfully reached the surface of Venus and carried out geochemical measurements using X-ray fluorescence and gamma-ray analysis.
[src:aaron-c-waters/basalt] These returned results consistent with the rock at the landing sites being basalts, including both tholeiitic and highly alkaline basalts.
[src:aaron-c-waters/basalt] The landers are thought to have landed on plains whose radar signature is that of basaltic lava flows.
[src:aaron-c-waters/basalt] These constitute about 80% of the surface of Venus.
[src:aaron-c-waters/basalt] Some locations show high reflectivity consistent with unweathered basalt, indicating basaltic volcanism within the last 2.5 million years.
[src:aaron-c-waters/basalt] Basalt is also a common rock on the surface of Mars, as determined by data sent back from the planet's surface, and by Martian meteorites.
[src:aaron-c-waters/basalt] Analysis of Hubble Space Telescope images of Vesta suggests this asteroid has a basaltic crust covered with a brecciated regolith derived from the crust.
[src:aaron-c-waters/basalt] Evidence from Earth-based telescopes and the Dawn mission suggest that Vesta is the source of the HED meteorites, which have basaltic characteristics.
[src:aaron-c-waters/basalt] Vesta is the main contributor to the inventory of basaltic asteroids of the main Asteroid Belt.
[src:aaron-c-waters/basalt] Lava flows represent a major volcanic terrain on Io.
[src:aaron-c-waters/basalt] Analysis of the *Voyager* images led scientists to believe that these flows were composed mostly of various compounds of molten sulfur.
[src:aaron-c-waters/basalt] However, subsequent Earth-based infrared studies and measurements from the *Galileo* spacecraft indicate that these flows are composed of basaltic lava with mafic to ultramafic compositions.
[src:aaron-c-waters/basalt] This conclusion is based on temperature measurements of Io's "hotspots", or thermal-emission locations, which suggest temperatures of at least 1,300 K and some as high as 1,600 K.
[src:aaron-c-waters/basalt] Initial estimates suggesting eruption temperatures approaching 2,000 K have since proven to be overestimates because the wrong thermal models were used to model the temperatures.
[src:aaron-c-waters/basalt] Compared to granitic rocks exposed at the Earth's surface, basalt outcrops weather relatively rapidly.
[src:aaron-c-waters/basalt] This reflects their content of minerals that crystallized at higher temperatures and in an environment poorer in water vapor than granite.
[src:aaron-c-waters/basalt] These minerals are less stable in the colder, wetter environment at the Earth's surface.
[src:aaron-c-waters/basalt] The finer grain size of basalt and the volcanic glass sometimes found between the grains also hasten weathering.
[src:aaron-c-waters/basalt] The high iron content of basalt causes weathered surfaces in humid climates to accumulate a thick crust of hematite or other iron oxides and hydroxides, staining the rock a brown to rust-red colour.
[src:aaron-c-waters/basalt] Because of the low potassium content of most basalts, weathering converts the basalt to calcium-rich clay (montmorillonite) rather than potassium-rich clay (illite).
[src:aaron-c-waters/basalt] Further weathering, particularly in tropical climates, converts the montmorillonite to kaolinite or gibbsite.
[src:aaron-c-waters/basalt] This produces the distinctive tropical soil known as laterite.
[src:aaron-c-waters/basalt] The ultimate weathering product is bauxite, the principal ore of aluminium.
[src:aaron-c-waters/basalt] In humid tropical areas, weathering of basalt and other basic crystalline rocks produces high yields of aluminium and iron oxides to the soils that develop, placing them in the oxisol soil order.
[src:aaron-c-waters/basalt] Chemical weathering also releases readily water-soluble cations such as calcium, sodium and magnesium, which give basaltic areas a strong buffer capacity against acidification.
[src:aaron-c-waters/basalt] Calcium released by basalts binds CO2 from the atmosphere forming CaCO3 acting thus as a CO2 trap.
[src:aaron-c-waters/basalt] Intense heat or great pressure transforms basalt into its metamorphic rock equivalents.
[src:aaron-c-waters/basalt] Depending on the temperature and pressure of metamorphism, these may include greenschist, amphibolite, or eclogite.
[src:aaron-c-waters/basalt] Basalts are important rocks within metamorphic regions because they can provide vital information on the conditions of metamorphism that have affected the region.
[src:aaron-c-waters/basalt] Metamorphosed basalts are important hosts for a variety of hydrothermal ores, including deposits of gold, copper and volcanogenic massive sulfides.
[src:aaron-c-waters/basalt] The common corrosion features of underwater volcanic basalt suggest that microbial activity may play a significant role in the chemical exchange between basaltic rocks and seawater.
[src:aaron-c-waters/basalt] The significant amounts of reduced iron, Fe(II), and manganese, Mn(II), present in basaltic rocks provide potential energy sources for bacteria.
[src:aaron-c-waters/basalt] Some Fe(II)-oxidizing bacteria cultured from iron-sulfide surfaces are also able to grow with basaltic rock as a source of Fe(II).
[src:aaron-c-waters/basalt] Fe- and Mn- oxidizing bacteria have been cultured from weathered submarine basalts of Kamaʻehuakanaloa Seamount (formerly Loihi).
[src:aaron-c-waters/basalt] The impact of bacteria on altering the chemical composition of basaltic glass (and thus, the oceanic crust) and seawater suggest that these interactions may lead to an application of hydrothermal vents to the origin of life.
[src:aaron-c-waters/basalt] Basalt is used in construction (e.g. as building blocks or in the groundwork), making cobblestones (from columnar basalt) and in making statues.
[src:aaron-c-waters/basalt] Heating and extruding basalt yields stone wool, which has potential to be an excellent thermal insulator.
[src:aaron-c-waters/basalt] Carbon sequestration in basalt has been studied as a means of removing carbon dioxide, produced by human industrialization, from the atmosphere.
[src:aaron-c-waters/basalt] Underwater basalt deposits, scattered in seas around the globe, have the added benefit of the water serving as a barrier to the re-release of CO2 into the atmosphere.
[src:aaron-c-waters/batholith] A **batholith** (from Ancient Greek βαθύς (*bathús*), meaning "deep", and λίθος (*líthos*), meaning "stone") is a large mass of intrusive igneous rock (also called plutonic rock), larger than 100 km2 (40 sq mi) in area, that forms from cooled magma deep in the Earth's crust.
[src:aaron-c-waters/batholith] Batholiths are almost always made mostly of felsic or intermediate rock types, such as granite, quartz monzonite, or diorite (see also *granite dome*).
[src:aaron-c-waters/batholith] Although they may appear uniform, batholiths are in fact structures with complex histories and compositions.
[src:aaron-c-waters/batholith] They are composed of multiple masses, or *plutons*, bodies of igneous rock of irregular dimensions (typically at least several kilometers) that can be distinguished from adjacent igneous rock by some combination of criteria including age, composition, texture, or mappable structures.
[src:aaron-c-waters/batholith] Individual plutons are solidified from magma that traveled toward the surface from a zone of partial melting near the base of the Earth's crust.
[src:aaron-c-waters/batholith] Traditionally, these plutons have been considered to form by ascent of relatively buoyant magma in large masses called *plutonic diapirs*.
[src:aaron-c-waters/batholith] Because the diapirs are liquified and very hot, they tend to rise through the surrounding native country rock, pushing it aside and partially melting it.
[src:aaron-c-waters/batholith] Most diapirs do not reach the surface to form volcanoes, but instead they slow down, cool, and usually solidify 5 to 30 kilometers underground as plutons (hence the use of the word *pluton*; in reference to the Roman god of the underworld Pluto).
[src:aaron-c-waters/batholith] An alternate view is that plutons are formed by aggregation of smaller volumes of magma that ascend as dikes.
[src:aaron-c-waters/batholith] A batholith is formed when many plutons converge to form a huge expanse of granitic rock.
[src:aaron-c-waters/batholith] Some batholiths are mammoth, paralleling past and present subduction zones and other heat sources for hundreds of kilometers in continental crust.
[src:aaron-c-waters/batholith] One such batholith is the Sierra Nevada Batholith, which is a continuous granitic formation that makes up much of the Sierra Nevada in California.
[src:aaron-c-waters/batholith] An even larger batholith, the Coast Plutonic Complex, is found predominantly in the Coast Mountains of western Canada; it extends for 1,800 kilometers and reaches into southeastern Alaska.
[src:aaron-c-waters/batholith] A batholith is an exposed area of (mostly) continuous plutonic rock that covers an area larger than 100 square kilometers (40 square miles).
[src:aaron-c-waters/batholith] Areas smaller than 100 square kilometers are called *stocks*.
[src:aaron-c-waters/batholith] However, the majority of batholiths visible at the surface (via outcroppings) have areas far greater than 100 square kilometers.
[src:aaron-c-waters/batholith] These areas are exposed to the surface through the process of erosion accelerated by continental uplift acting over many tens of millions to hundreds of millions of years.
[src:aaron-c-waters/batholith] This process has removed several tens of square kilometers of overlying rock in many areas, exposing the once deeply buried batholiths.
[src:aaron-c-waters/batholith] Batholiths exposed at the surface are subjected to huge pressure differences between their former location deep in the earth and their new location at or near the surface.
[src:aaron-c-waters/batholith] As a result, their crystal structure expands slightly over time.
[src:aaron-c-waters/batholith] This manifests itself by a form of mass wasting called exfoliation.
[src:aaron-c-waters/batholith] This form of weathering causes convex and relatively thin sheets of rock to slough off the exposed surfaces of batholiths (a process accelerated by frost wedging).
[src:aaron-c-waters/batholith] The result is fairly clean and rounded rock faces.
[src:aaron-c-waters/batholith] A well-known result of this process is Half Dome in Yosemite Valley.
